{"title_page": "Noum\u00e9a", "text_new": "{{short description|Capital of New Caledonia}}\n{{Redirect|Noumea|the genus of sea slugs|Noumea (gastropod)|the language|Ndrumbea language}}\n{{Infobox French commune\n|name                   = Noum\u00e9a\n|commune status         = [[Communes of France|Commune]]\n|image                  = Noumea centre 1402561139 375c811796 o.jpg\n|caption                = City centre and [[Noum\u00e9a Cathedral]]\n|image coat of arms     = Armoiries Noum\u00e9an fr.png\n|map size               = 270px\n|adjustable map         = noumea.PNG\n|map caption            = Location of the commune (in red)<br>within New Caledonia\n|province               = [[South Province, New Caledonia|South Province]]<br>(provincial seat)\n|INSEE                  = 98818\n|postal code            = 98800\n|mayor                  = [[Sonia Lagarde]]\n|term                   = 2014\u2013present\n|coordinates            = {{coord|-22.2758|166.4580|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation m            = 20\n|elevation min m        = 0\n|elevation max m        = 167\n|area km2               = 45.7\n|urban area km2         = 1,643\n|area footnotes         = <ref name=area>{{cite web|url=http://www.isee.nc/tec/atlas/telechargements/1-territoire-environnement.pdf|title=Tableaux de l'\u00e9conomie cal\u00e9donienne, Chapitre 1 : TERRITOIRE-ENVIRONNEMENT|publisher=ISEE|year=2012|accessdate=2013-10-14|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113161955/http://www.isee.nc/tec/atlas/telechargements/1-territoire-environnement.pdf|archivedate=13 November 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|population             = 94285\n|urban pop              = 182341\n|population date        = 2019 Census<ref>http://www.isee.nc/component/phocadownload/category/195-donnees?download=768:la-population-legale</ref>\n|ethnic                 = [[European ethnic groups|European]]s 43.23%<br>[[Kanak people|Kanak]]s 23.79%<br>Wallisians and Futunans 6.67%<br>[[Multiracial|Mixed]] 7.87%<br>Other 18.44%\n|ethnic date            = 2014 census\n}}\n\n[[File:Flag of the city of Noum\u00e9a, New Caledonia.png|thumb|upright|Noum\u00e9a city flag, 2011]]\n\n'''Noum\u00e9a''' ({{IPA-fr|numea}}) is the [[capital city|capital]] and largest city of the [[France|French]] [[sui generis collectivity|special collectivity]] of [[New Caledonia]]. It is situated on a peninsula in the south of New Caledonia's main island, [[Grande Terre (New Caledonia)|Grande Terre]], and is home to the majority of the island's [[Europe]]an, [[Polynesia]]n ([[Wallis and Futuna|Wallisians]], [[Wallis and Futuna|Futunians]], [[Tahiti]]ans), [[Indonesia]]n, and [[Vietnamese people|Vietnamese]] populations, as well as many [[Melanesian]]s, [[Ni-Vanuatu]] and [[Kanak people|Kanak]]s who work in one of the [[Oceania|South Pacific]]'s most [[industrialisation|industrialised]] cities. The city lies on a protected deepwater harbour that serves as the chief port for New Caledonia.\n\nAt the September 2019 census, there were 182,341 inhabitants in the metropolitan area of Greater Noum\u00e9a ({{Lang-fr|agglom\u00e9ration du Grand Noum\u00e9a}}), 94,285 of whom lived in the city ([[communes of France|commune]]) of Noum\u00e9a proper.<ref name=pop>{{cite web|url=http://www.isee.nc/component/phocadownload/category/194-structure-de-la-population-et-evolutions?download=1329:population-legale-2014|title=Recensement de la population 2014 - Populations l\u00e9gales 2014|publisher=ISEE|accessdate=2014-11-16|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20150419171546/http://www.isee.nc/component/phocadownload/category/194-structure-de-la-population-et-evolutions?download=1329:population-legale-2014|archivedate=19 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> 67.2% of the population of New Caledonia live in Greater Noum\u00e9a, which covers the communes of Noum\u00e9a, [[Le Mont-Dore (New Caledonia)|Le Mont-Dore]], [[Dumb\u00e9a]] and [[Pa\u00efta]].\n\n==History==\nThe first European to establish a settlement in the vicinity was British trader [[James Paddon]] in 1851. Anxious to assert control of the island, the French established a settlement nearby three years later in 1854, moving from [[Balade (New Caledonia)|Balade]] in the north of the island. This settlement was initially called Port-de-France and was renamed Noum\u00e9a in 1866. The area served first as a [[penal colony]], later as a centre for the exportation of the [[nickel]] and [[gold]] that was mined nearby.\n\nFrom 1904 to 1940 Noum\u00e9a was linked to [[Dumb\u00e9a]] and [[Pa\u00efta]] by the [[Noum\u00e9a-Pa\u00efta railway]], the only railway line that ever existed in New Caledonia.\n\nDuring [[World War II]], Noum\u00e9a served as the headquarters of the [[United States]] military in the South Pacific. The five-sided U.S. military headquarters  complex was adopted after the war as the base for a new regional intergovernmental development organisation: the South Pacific Commission, later known as the [[Secretariat of the Pacific Community]], and later still as the Pacific Community.\n\nThe city maintains much of New Caledonia's unique mix of French and old Melanesian culture. Even today the [[United States|US]] wartime military influence lingers, both with the warmth that many New Caledonian people feel towards the United States after experiencing the relative friendliness of American soldiers and also with the names of several of the quarters in Noum\u00e9a. Districts such as \"Receiving\" and \"Robinson\", or even \"Motor Pool\", strike the [[English-speaking world|anglophone]] ear strangely, until the historical context becomes clear.\n\n==Geography==\nThe [[city]] is situated on an irregular, hilly [[peninsula]] near the southeast end of [[New Caledonia]], which is in the south-west [[Pacific Ocean]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2011}}\n\nNeighbourhoods of Noum\u00e9a include:<ref>\"[http://www.ville-noumea.nc/vivre/quartiers.asp Les quartiers] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722112059/http://www.ville-noumea.nc/vivre/quartiers.asp |date=22 July 2011 }}.\" Noum\u00e9a. Retrieved on 12 February 2011.</ref>\n*Rivi\u00e8re-Sal\u00e9e\n*6e km, 7e km, Normandie, and Tina\n*Ducos peninsula:\n**Ducos, Ducos industriel, Kam\u00e9r\u00e9, Koumourou, Logicoop, Numbo, Tindu\n*4e Km, A\u00e9rodrome, Haut Magenta, Magenta, Ou\u00e9mo, and Portes de fer\n*Faubourg Blanchot and Vall\u00e9e des Colons\n*Doniambo, Montagne coup\u00e9e, Montravel, and Vall\u00e9e du tir\n*Artillerie Nord, Centre Ville, Nouville, Quartier Latin, Vall\u00e9e du G\u00e9nie\n*Anse Vata, Artillerie Sud, Baie des Citrons, Motor Pool, N'g\u00e9a, Orphelinat, Receiving, Trianon, and Val Plaisance\n\n==Demographics==\n[[File:Noumea Market.jpg|thumb|250px|A woman at a market in Noum\u00e9a, 2006]]\nThe Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area ({{lang-fr|agglom\u00e9ration du Grand Noum\u00e9a|links=no}}) had a total population of 182,341 inhabitants at the September 2019 census, 94,285 of whom lived in the [[commune in France|commune]] of Noum\u00e9a proper.<ref>http://www.isee.nc/component/phocadownload/category/195-donnees?download=768:la-population-legale</ref>\n\nThe Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area is made up of four communes:\n*Noum\u00e9a (94,285 inh.)\n*[[Dumb\u00e9a]] (35,873 inh.), to the north-west of Noum\u00e9a\n*[[Le Mont-Dore (New Caledonia)|Le Mont-Dore]] (27,620 inh.), to the north-east of Noum\u00e9a\n*[[Pa\u00efta]] (24,563 inh.), a suburb to the west of Dumb\u00e9a and the site of [[La Tontouta International Airport]]\n\n===Historical population===\n\n{| rules=\"all\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"4\" style=\"margin:auto; border:1px solid #999; border-right:2px solid #999; border-bottom:2px solid #999; background:#f3fff3;\"\n|-\n! !! 1956!! 1963!! 1969 !! 1976 !! 1983 !! 1989 !! 1996!! 2009 !! 2014 !! 2019\n|-\n| align=center| '''Noum\u00e9a (commune)''' || align=center| 22,235 || align=center| 34,990 || align=center| 41,853 || align=center| 56,078 || align=center| 60,112 || align=center| 65,110 || align=center| 76,293 || align=center| 97,579 || align=center| 99,926 || align=center| 94,285\n|-\n| align=center| '''Greater Noum\u00e9a''' || align=center| 25,204 || align=center| 39,996 || align=center| 50,488 || align=center| 74,335 || align=center| 85,098 || align=center| 97,581 || align=center| 118,823 || align=center| 163,723 || align=center| 179,509 || align=center| 182,341\n|-\n| colspan=\"13\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <small>Official figures from population censuses.<ref name=pop /><ref name=RP56_09>{{cite web|url=http://www.isee.nc/population/telecharxls/pop-com-56-09.xls|title=Population des communes de la Nouvelle-Cal\u00e9donie de 1956 \u00e0 2009|publisher=ISEE|accessdate=2013-10-14|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121030182852/http://www.isee.nc/population/telecharxls/pop-com-56-09.xls|archivedate=30 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref></small>\n|}\n\nAverage population growth of the Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area:\n*1956-1963: +2,310 people per year (+7.5% per year)\n*1963-1969: +1,791 people per year (+4.1% per year)\n*1969-1976: +3,349 people per year (+5.6% per year)\n*1976-1983: +1,543 people per year (+2.0% per year)\n*1983-1989: +2,091 people per year (+2.3% per year)\n*1989-1996: +3,020 people per year (+2.8% per year)\n*1996-2009: +3,382 people per year (+2.4% per year)\n*2009-2014: +3,106 people per year (+1.8% per year)\n*2014-2019: +566 people per year (+0.3% per year)\n\n===Migrations===\nThe places of birth of the 179,509 residents in the Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area at the 2014 census were the following:<ref name=censusdetail>{{cite web|url=http://www.isee.nc/component/phocadownload/category/193-recensement?download=1442:rp-2014-population-logement-menages-communes|title=Recensement de la population de 2014 - Population, m\u00e9nages et logements par communes de Nouvelle Cal\u00e9donie|publisher=ISEE|accessdate=2018-01-02|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171025024348/http://www.isee.nc/component/phocadownload/category/193-recensement?download=1442:rp-2014-population-logement-menages-communes|archivedate=25 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*66.7% were born in New Caledonia\n*21.2% in [[Metropolitan France]] and its [[overseas department]]s (other than Wallis-and-Futuna and French Polynesia)\n*6.3% in foreign countries (notably [[Indonesia]], [[Vanuatu]], [[Vietnam]], and [[Algeria]])\n*5.8% in [[Wallis and Futuna]] (essentially) and [[French Polynesia]] (to a lesser extent)\n\n===Ethnic communities===\nThe self-reported ethnic communities of the 179,509 residents in the Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area at the 2014 census were as follows:<ref name=censusdetail />\n*34.48% [[White people|Europeans]]\n*23.43% [[Kanak people|Kanaks]] (original [[Melanesians|Melanesian]] inhabitants of New Caledonia)\n*11.53% [[Wallis and Futuna|Wallisians and Futunians]]\n*10.05% [[multiracial|mixed ethnicity]]\n*20.51% other communities (this group includes in particular the White people of New Caledonia who refused to self-identify as \"Europeans\")\n\n===Languages===\nAt the 2009 census, 98.7% of the population in the Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area whose age was 15 years old and older reported that they could speak [[French language|French]]. 97.1% reported that they could also read and write it. Only 1.3% of the population whose age was 15 years old and older had no knowledge of French.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.isee.nc/population/telecharxls/commune-prov-rp-2009.xls|title=P19 Population de 15 ans et plus, selon le sexe et la connaissance du fran\u00e7ais, par commune et province de r\u00e9sidence|publisher=ISEE|accessdate=2013-10-14|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017182011/http://www.isee.nc/population/telecharxls/commune-prov-rp-2009.xls|archivedate=17 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAt the same census, 20.8% of the population in the Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area whose age was 15 years old and older reported that they could speak at least one of the [[New Caledonian languages|Kanak languages]]. 4.3% reported that they could understand a Kanak language but not speak it. 74.9% of the population whose age was 15 years old and older had no knowledge of any Kanak language.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.isee.nc/population/telecharxls/commune-prov-rp-2009.xls|title=P21 Population de 15 ans et plus, selon le sexe et la connaissance d'une langue kanak, par commune et province de r\u00e9sidence|publisher=ISEE|accessdate=2013-10-14|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017182011/http://www.isee.nc/population/telecharxls/commune-prov-rp-2009.xls|archivedate=17 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Climate==\nNoum\u00e9a features a [[tropical wet and dry climate]] with hot summers and warm winters. Temperatures are warmer in the months of January, February and March with average highs hovering around 30 degrees Celsius and cooler during the months of July and August where average high temperatures are around 23 degrees Celsius. The capital's [[dry season]] months are September and October. The rest of the year is noticeably wetter. Noum\u00e9a on average receives roughly {{convert|1100|mm|0|abbr=on}} of precipitation annually.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Noumea, New Caledonia\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n|Jan high C = 28.9\n|Feb high C = 29.0\n|Mar high C = 28.5\n|Apr high C = 26.9\n|May high C = 25.2\n|Jun high C = 23.8\n|Jul high C = 22.6\n|Aug high C = 22.8\n|Sep high C = 23.8\n|Oct high C = 25.5\n|Nov high C = 27.0\n|Dec high C = 28.2\n|Jan mean C = 26.0\n|Feb mean C = 26.1\n|Mar mean C = 25.6\n|Apr mean C = 24.1\n|May mean C = 22.5\n|Jun mean C = 21.1\n|Jul mean C = 20.0\n|Aug mean C = 20.5\n|Sep mean C = 21.1\n|Oct mean C = 22.4\n|Nov mean C = 23.9\n|Dec mean C = 25.0\n|Jan low C = 23.0\n|Feb low C = 23.2\n|Mar low C = 22.8\n|Apr low C = 21.4\n|May low C = 19.8\n|Jun low C = 18.5\n|Jul low C = 17.3\n|Aug low C = 17.5\n|Sep low C =