national airline of New Caledonia,<ref>\"[http://us.aircalin.com/contact-aircalin.php Contact Us] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090601195747/http://us.aircalin.com/contact-aircalin.php |date=1 June 2009 }}.\" [[Aircalin]]. Retrieved on 2 October 2009.</ref> and [[Air Cal\u00e9donie]] (Aircal), the domestic airline, have their headquarters in the city.<ref>\"[http://air-caledonie.nc:8080/en/ukcontact.htm AIR CAL\u00c9DONIE CONTACTS]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.\" [[Air Cal\u00e9donie]]. Retrieved on 2 October 2009.</ref> Aircal's headquarters are on the grounds of [[Noum\u00e9a Magenta Airport]],<ref>\"[http://www.air-caledonie.nc/fr/pdf/carte_renew_nb.pdf Renouvellement de Carte R\u00e9sident] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090530002353/http://www.air-caledonie.nc/fr/pdf/carte_renew_nb.pdf |date=30 May 2009 }}.\" Air Cal\u00e9donie. Retrieved on 8 October 2009.</ref>\nwhich serves local routes. Noum\u00e9a's international airport is [[La Tontouta International Airport]], {{convert|50|km|mi}} from the city.\n\nThe [[Noum\u00e9a-Pa\u00efta railway]], which was the only railway line that ever existed in New Caledonia, was closed in 1940.\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Main building at Nouville campus, University of New Caledonia.png|thumb|250px|[[University of New Caledonia]], Nouville campus]]\n[[File:Exterior view of Bernheim Library, Noum\u00e9a.png|thumb|250px|Bernheim Library exterior]]\n[[File:Interior View 2 of Bernheim Library, Noumea.png|thumb|250px|Bernheim Library interior]]\nThe [[University of New Caledonia]]  (UNC) goes back to 1987 when the Universit\u00e9 Fran\u00e7aise du Pacifique (French University of the Pacific) was created, with two centres, one in French Polynesia and the other in New Caledonia. In 1997 the decision was made to split the two parts into separate universities and so in 1999 the Universit\u00e9 de la Nouvelle Cal\u00e9donie and the Universit\u00e9 de la Polyn\u00e9sie Fran\u00e7aise were formed.\n\nUNC welcomes around 3,000 local and international students and 100 professors and researchers each year.<ref>\"{{cite web |url=http://www.univ-nc.nc/propos-de-lunc/presentation |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-01-05 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119221009/http://www.univ-nc.nc/propos-de-lunc/presentation |archivedate=19 January 2012 |df=dmy-all }} Universit\u00e9 de la Nouvelle-Cal\u00e9donie. Retrieved on 5 January 2012.</ref>\n\nThe ''Biblioth\u00e8que Bernheim'' (Bernheim Library) is located in Noum\u00e9a.<ref>\"[http://www.bernheim.nc/distribution.asp?page=information/vico.asp&inter=0&num=5&parcours=information/paco.asp coordonn\u00e9es & horaires] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110316185105/http://www.bernheim.nc/distribution.asp?page=information%2Fvico.asp&inter=0&num=5&parcours=information%2Fpaco.asp |date=16 March 2011 }}.\" Biblioth\u00e8que Bernheim. Retrieved on 12 February 2011.</ref>\n\n==Twin towns \u2013 sister cities==\n*{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]] ([[Australia]])\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Nice]] ([[Metropolitan France|Metropolitan]] [[France]])<ref name=\"Nice Jumellage\">{{cite web | url = http://www.nice.fr/Collectivites/La-municipalite/Villes-jumelees-avec-la-Ville-de-Nice | title = Villes jumel\u00e9es avec la Ville de Nice | accessdate = 2013-06-24 | publisher = Ville de Nice | language = French | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121029114949/http://nice.fr/Collectivites/La-municipalite/Villes-jumelees-avec-la-Ville-de-Nice | archivedate = 29 October 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|NZL}} [[Taupo]] ([[New Zealand]])\n\n==Popular culture==\n* New Caledonia was the favorite liberty port in the Pacific of the crew of the ''PT-73'' in the American television series ''[[McHale's Navy]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pro.imdb.com/title/tt0055689/trivia |title=IMDbPro |publisher=Pro.imdb.com |date= |accessdate=2017-11-06}}</ref>\n* Sydney-based author Nathan J. Roche set his 2014 novel ''The Noum\u00e9a Neurosis'', a satirical prose account of cycling, in and around Noum\u00e9a.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thethousands.com.au/sydney/read/nathan-j-roche-the-noumea-neurosis--2 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-01-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170108190232/http://thethousands.com.au/sydney/read/nathan-j-roche-the-noumea-neurosis--2 |archivedate=8 January 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Noum\u00e9a}}\n*{{Wikivoyage-inline}}\n*[http://www.newcaledoniatourism-south.com/ Tourism New Caledonia (South)]\n*{{in lang|fr}} {{Official website|/www.ville-noumea.nc|Noum\u00e9a's official municipal website}}\n*{{in lang|fr}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20050328065902/http://www.ac-noumea.nc/laperouse/site-hg/site/ Noum\u00e9a: Commune Fran\u00e7aise du Bout du Monde] \u2013 a school project on the geography and history of Noum\u00e9a\n\n{{Administrative divisions of New Caledonia}}\n{{List of Oceanian capitals by region}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2011}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Noumea}}\n[[Category:Noum\u00e9a| ]]\n[[Category:Capitals in Oceania]]\n[[Category:Communes of New Caledonia]]\n[[Category:Port cities in Oceania]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Capital of New Caledonia}}\n{{Redirect|Noumea|the genus of sea slugs|Noumea (gastropod)|the language|Ndrumbea language}}\n{{Infobox French commune\n|name                   = Noum\u00e9a\n|commune status         = [[Communes of France|Commune]]\n|image                  = Noumea centre 1402561139 375c811796 o.jpg\n|caption                = City centre and [[Noum\u00e9a Cathedral]]\n|image coat of arms     = Armoiries Noum\u00e9an fr.png\n|map size               = 300px\n|adjustable map         = noumea.PNG\n|map caption            = Location of the commune (in red)<br>within New Caledonia\n|province               = [[South Province, New Caledonia|South Province]]<br>(provincial seat)\n|INSEE                  = 98818\n|postal code            = 98800\n|mayor                  = [[Sonia Lagarde]]\n|term                   = 2014\u2013present\n|coordinates            = {{coord|-22.2758|166.4580|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation m            = 20\n|elevation min m        = 0\n|elevation max m        = 167\n|area km2               = 45.7\n|urban area km2         = 1,643\n|area footnotes         = <ref name=area>{{cite web|url=http://www.isee.nc/tec/atlas/telechargements/1-territoire-environnement.pdf|title=Tableaux de l'\u00e9conomie cal\u00e9donienne, Chapitre 1 : TERRITOIRE-ENVIRONNEMENT|publisher=ISEE|year=2012|accessdate=2013-10-14|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113161955/http://www.isee.nc/tec/atlas/telechargements/1-territoire-environnement.pdf|archivedate=13 November 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|population             = 94285\n|urban pop              = 182341\n|population date        = 2019 Census<ref>http://www.isee.nc/component/phocadownload/category/195-donnees?download=768:la-population-legale</ref>\n|ethnic                 = [[European ethnic groups|European]]s 43.23%<br>[[Kanak people|Kanak]]s 23.79%<br>Wallisians and Futunans 6.67%<br>[[Multiracial|Mixed]] 7.87%<br>Other 18.44%\n|ethnic date            = 2014 census\n}}\n\n[[File:Flag of the city of Noum\u00e9a, New Caledonia.png|thumb|upright|Noum\u00e9a city flag, 2011]]\n\n'''Noum\u00e9a''' ({{IPA-fr|numea}}) is the [[capital city|capital]] and largest city of the [[France|French]] [[sui generis collectivity|special collectivity]] of [[New Caledonia]]. It is situated on a peninsula in the south of New Caledonia's main island, [[Grande Terre (New Caledonia)|Grande Terre]], and is home to the majority of the island's [[Europe]]an, [[Polynesia]]n ([[Wallis and Futuna|Wallisians]], [[Wallis and Futuna|Futunians]], [[Tahiti]]ans), [[Indonesia]]n, and [[Vietnamese people|Vietnamese]] populations, as well as many [[Melanesian]]s, [[Ni-Vanuatu]] and [[Kanak people|Kanak]]s who work in one of the [[Oceania|South Pacific]]'s most [[industrialisation|industrialised]] cities. The city lies on a protected deepwater harbour that serves as the chief port for New Caledonia.\n\nAt the September 2019 census, there were 182,341 inhabitants in the metropolitan area of Greater Noum\u00e9a ({{Lang-fr|agglom\u00e9ration du Grand Noum\u00e9a}}), 94,285 of whom lived in the city ([[communes of France|commune]]) of Noum\u00e9a proper.<ref name=pop>{{cite web|url=http://www.isee.nc/component/phocadownload/category/194-structure-de-la-population-et-evolutions?download=1329:population-legale-2014|title=Recensement de la population 2014 - Populations l\u00e9gales 2014|publisher=ISEE|accessdate=2014-11-16|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20150419171546/http://www.isee.nc/component/phocadownload/category/194-structure-de-la-population-et-evolutions?download=1329:population-legale-2014|archivedate=19 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> 67.2% of the population of New Caledonia live in Greater Noum\u00e9a, which covers the communes of Noum\u00e9a, [[Le Mont-Dore (New Caledonia)|Le Mont-Dore]], [[Dumb\u00e9a]] and [[Pa\u00efta]].\n\n==History==\nThe first European to establish a settlement in the vicinity was British trader [[James Paddon]] in 1851. Anxious to assert control of the island, the French established a settlement nearby three years later in 1854, moving from [[Balade (New Caledonia)|Balade]] in the north of the island. This settlement was initially called Port-de-France and was renamed Noum\u00e9a in 1866. The area served first as a [[penal colony]], later as a centre for the exportation of the [[nickel]] and [[gold]] that was mined nearby.\n\nFrom 1904 to 1940 Noum\u00e9a was linked to [[Dumb\u00e9a]] and [[Pa\u00efta]] by the [[Noum\u00e9a-Pa\u00efta railway]], the only railway line that ever existed in New Caledonia.\n\nDuring [[World War II]], Noum\u00e9a served as the headquarters of the [[United States]] military in the South Pacific. The five-sided U.S. military headquarters  complex was adopted after the war as the base for a new regional intergovernmental development organisation: the South Pacific Commission, later known as the [[Secretariat of the Pacific Community]], and later still as the Pacific Community.\n\nThe city maintains much of New Caledonia's unique mix of French and old Melanesian culture. Even today the [[United States|US]] wartime military influence lingers, both with the warmth that many New Caledonian people feel towards the United States after experiencing the relative friendliness of American soldiers and also with the names of several of the quarters in Noum\u00e9a. Districts such as \"Receiving\" and \"Robinson\", or even \"Motor Pool\", strike the [[English-speaking world|anglophone]] ear strangely, until the historical context becomes clear.\n\n==Geography==\nThe [[city]] is situated on an irregular, hilly [[peninsula]] near the southeast end of [[New Caledonia]], which is in the south-west [[Pacific Ocean]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2011}}\n\nNeighbourhoods of Noum\u00e9a include:<ref>\"[http://www.ville-noumea.nc/vivre/quartiers.asp Les quartiers] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722112059/http://www.ville-noumea.nc/vivre/quartiers.asp |date=22 July 2011 }}.\" Noum\u00e9a. Retrieved on 12 February 2011.</ref>\n*Rivi\u00e8re-Sal\u00e9e\n*6e km, 7e km, Normandie, and Tina\n*Ducos peninsula:\n**Ducos, Ducos industriel, Kam\u00e9r\u00e9, Koumourou, Logicoop, Numbo, Tindu\n*4e Km, A\u00e9rodrome, Haut Magenta, Magenta, Ou\u00e9mo, and Portes de fer\n*Faubourg Blanchot and Vall\u00e9e des Colons\n*Doniambo, Montagne coup\u00e9e, Montravel, and Vall\u00e9e du tir\n*Artillerie Nord, Centre Ville, Nouville, Quartier Latin, Vall\u00e9e du G\u00e9nie\n*Anse Vata, Artillerie Sud, Baie des Citrons, Motor Pool, N'g\u00e9a, Orphelinat, Receiving, Trianon, and Val Plaisance\n\n==Demographics==\n[[File:Noumea Market.jpg|thumb|250px|A woman at a market in Noum\u00e9a, 2006]]\nThe Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area ({{lang-fr|agglom\u00e9ration du Grand Noum\u00e9a|links=no}}) had a total population of 182,341 inhabitants at the September 2019 census, 94,285 of whom lived in the [[commune in France|commune]] of Noum\u00e9a proper.<ref>http://www.isee.nc/component/phocadownload/category/195-donnees?download=768:la-population-legale</ref>\n\nThe Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area is made up of four communes:\n*Noum\u00e9a (94,285 inh.)\n*[[Dumb\u00e9a]] (35,873 inh.), to the north-west of Noum\u00e9a\n*[[Le Mont-Dore (New Caledonia)|Le Mont-Dore]] (27,620 inh.), to the north-east of Noum\u00e9a\n*[[Pa\u00efta]] (24,563 inh.), a suburb to the west of Dumb\u00e9a and the site of [[La Tontouta International Airport]]\n\n===Historical population===\n\n{| rules=\"all\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"4\" style=\"margin:auto; border:1px solid #999; border-right:2px solid #999; border-bottom:2px solid #999; background:#f3fff3;\"\n|-\n! !! 1956!! 1963!! 1969 !! 1976 !! 1983 !! 1989 !! 1996!! 2009 !! 2014 !! 2019\n|-\n| align=center| '''Noum\u00e9a (commune)''' || align=center| 22,235 || align=center| 34,990 || align=center| 41,853 || align=center| 56,078 || align=center| 60,112 || align=center| 65,110 || align=center| 76,293 || align=center| 97,579 || align=center| 99,926 || align=center| 94,285\n|-\n| align=center| '''Greater Noum\u00e9a''' || align=center| 25,204 || align=center| 39,996 || align=center| 50,488 || align=center| 74,335 || align=center| 85,098 || align=center| 97,581 || align=center| 118,823 || align=center| 163,723 || align=center| 179,509 || align=center| 182,341\n|-\n| colspan=\"13\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| <small>Official figures from population censuses.<ref name=pop /><ref name=RP56_09>{{cite web|url=http://www.isee.nc/population/telecharxls/pop-com-56-09.xls|title=Population des communes de la Nouvelle-Cal\u00e9donie de 1956 \u00e0 2009|publisher=ISEE|accessdate=2013-10-14|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121030182852/http://www.isee.nc/population/telecharxls/pop-com-56-09.xls|archivedate=30 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref></small>\n|}\n\nAverage population growth of the Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area:\n*1956-1963: +2,310 people per year (+7.5% per year)\n*1963-1969: +1,791 people per year (+4.1% per year)\n*1969-1976: +3,349 people per year (+5.6% per year)\n*1976-1983: +1,543 people per year (+2.0% per year)\n*1983-1989: +2,091 people per year (+2.3% per year)\n*1989-1996: +3,020 people per year (+2.8% per year)\n*1996-2009: +3,382 people per year (+2.4% per year)\n*2009-2014: +3,106 people per year (+1.8% per year)\n*2014-2019: +566 people per year (+0.3% per year)\n\n===Migrations===\nThe places of birth of the 179,509 residents in the Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area at the 2014 census were the following:<ref name=censusdetail>{{cite web|url=http://www.isee.nc/component/phocadownload/category/193-recensement?download=1442:rp-2014-population-logement-menages-communes|title=Recensement de la population de 2014 - Population, m\u00e9nages et logements par communes de Nouvelle Cal\u00e9donie|publisher=ISEE|accessdate=2018-01-02|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171025024348/http://www.isee.nc/component/phocadownload/category/193-recensement?download=1442:rp-2014-population-logement-menages-communes|archivedate=25 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*66.7% were born in New Caledonia\n*21.2% in [[Metropolitan France]] and its [[overseas department]]s (other than Wallis-and-Futuna and French Polynesia)\n*6.3% in foreign countries (notably [[Indonesia]], [[Vanuatu]], [[Vietnam]], and [[Algeria]])\n*5.8% in [[Wallis and Futuna]] (essentially) and [[French Polynesia]] (to a lesser extent)\n\n===Ethnic communities===\nThe self-reported ethnic communities of the 179,509 residents in the Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area at the 2014 census were as follows:<ref name=censusdetail />\n*34.48% [[White people|Europeans]]\n*23.43% [[Kanak people|Kanaks]] (original [[Melanesians|Melanesian]] inhabitants of New Caledonia)\n*11.53% [[Wallis and Futuna|Wallisians and Futunians]]\n*10.05% [[multiracial|mixed ethnicity]]\n*20.51% other communities (this group includes in particular the White people of New Caledonia who refused to self-identify as \"Europeans\")\n\n===Languages===\nAt the 2009 census, 98.7% of the population in the Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area whose age was 15 years old and older reported that they could speak [[French language|French]]. 97.1% reported that they could also read and write it. Only 1.3% of the population whose age was 15 years old and older had no knowledge of French.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.isee.nc/population/telecharxls/commune-prov-rp-2009.xls|title=P19 Population de 15 ans et plus, selon le sexe et la connaissance du fran\u00e7ais, par commune et province de r\u00e9sidence|publisher=ISEE|accessdate=2013-10-14|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017182011/http://www.isee.nc/population/telecharxls/commune-prov-rp-2009.xls|archivedate=17 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAt the same census, 20.8% of the population in the Greater Noum\u00e9a urban area whose age was 15 years old and older reported that they could speak at least one of the [[New Caledonian languages|Kanak languages]]. 4.3% reported that they could understand a Kanak language but not speak it. 74.9% of the population whose age was 15 years old and older had no knowledge of any Kanak language.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.isee.nc/population/telecharxls/commune-prov-rp-2009.xls|title=P21 Population de 15 ans et plus, selon le sexe et la connaissance d'une langue kanak, par commune et province de r\u00e9sidence|publisher=ISEE|accessdate=2013-10-14|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017182011/http://www.isee.nc/population/telecharxls/commune-prov-rp-2009.xls|archivedate=17 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Climate==\nNoum\u00e9a features a [[tropical wet and dry climate]] with hot summers and warm winters. Temperatures are warmer in the months of January, February and March with average highs hovering around 30 degrees Celsius and cooler during the months of July and August where average high temperatures are around 23 degrees Celsius. The capital's [[dry season]] months are September and October. The rest of the year is noticeably wetter. Noum\u00e9a on average receives roughly {{convert|1100|mm|0|abbr=on}} of precipitation annually.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Noumea, New Caledonia\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n|Jan high C = 28.9\n|Feb high C = 29.0\n|Mar high C = 28.5\n|Apr high C = 26.9\n|May high C = 25.2\n|Jun high C = 23.8\n|Jul high C = 22.6\n|Aug high C = 22.8\n|Sep high C = 23.8\n|Oct high C = 25.5\n|Nov high C = 27.0\n|Dec high C = 28.2\n|Jan mean C = 26.0\n|Feb mean C = 26.1\n|Mar mean C = 25.6\n|Apr mean C = 24.1\n|May mean C = 22.5\n|Jun mean C = 21.1\n|Jul mean C = 20.0\n|Aug mean C = 20.5\n|Sep mean C = 21.1\n|Oct mean C = 22.4\n|Nov mean C = 23.9\n|Dec mean C = 25.0\n|Jan low C = 23.0\n|Feb low C = 23.2\n|Mar low C = 22.8\n|Apr low C = 21.4\n|May low C = 19.8\n|Jun low C = 18.5\n|Jul low C = 17.3\n|Aug low C = 17.5\n|Sep low C = 17.9\n|Oct low C = 19.2\n|Nov low C = 20.7\n|Dec low C = 21.9\n|Jan precipitation mm = 112.9\n|Feb precipitation mm = 123.1\n|Mar precipitation mm = 134.6\n|Apr precipitation mm = 110.5\n|May precipitation mm = 90.6\n|Jun precipitation mm = 128.7\n|Jul precipitation mm = 73.0\n|Aug precipitation mm = 70.1\n|Sep precipitation mm = 39.2\n|Oct precipitation mm = 53.2\n|Nov precipitation mm = 62.9\n|Dec precipitation mm = 72.7\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation days = 14.2\n|Feb precipitation days = 14.2\n|Mar precipitation days = 17.1\n|Apr precipitation days = 15.0\n|May precipitation days = 16.8\n|Jun precipitation days = 17.3\n|Jul precipitation days = 15.9\n|Aug precipitation days = 13.1\n|Sep precipitation days = 9.6\n|Oct precipitation days = 9.3\n|Nov precipitation days = 10.3\n|Dec precipitation days = 11.3\n|Jan sun = 232.5\n|Feb sun = 209.0\n|Mar sun = 201.5\n|Apr sun = 198.0\n|May sun = 176.7\n|Jun sun = 156.0\n|Jul sun = 182.9\n|Aug sun = 201.5\n|Sep sun = 222.0\n|Oct sun = 251.1\n|Nov sun = 249.0\n|Dec sun = 260.4\n|source 1 = Hong Kong Observatory<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weather.gov.hk/wxinfo/climat/world/eng/australia/pacific/noumea_e.htm|title=Climatological Information for Noumea, New Caledonia|publisher=Hong Kong Observatory|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320072343/http://www.weather.gov.hk/wxinfo/climat/world/eng/australia/pacific/noumea_e.htm|archivedate=20 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>|date=August 2010}}\n\n==Economy==\nAlthough Noum\u00e9a has more sunshine days than any other Pacific Island capital and beaches not far from the city centre, it is not currently a major tourist destination. \n\nNoum\u00e9a is, {{As of|2007|lc=y}}, one of the most rapidly growing cities in the Pacific and has experienced a major housing construction boom in the preceding decade. The installation of amenities has kept pace and the municipality boasts a public works programme.\n\n==Transport==\n[[Aircalin]], the international airline of New Caledonia,<ref>\"[http://us.aircalin.com/contact-aircalin.php Contact Us] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090601195747/http://us.aircalin.com/contact-aircalin.php |date=1 June 2009 }}.\" [[Aircalin]]. Retrieved on 2 October 2009.</ref> and [[Air Cal\u00e9donie]] (Aircal), the domestic airline, have their headquarters in the city.<ref>\"[http://air-caledonie.nc:8080/en/ukcontact.htm AIR CAL\u00c9DONIE CONTACTS]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.\" [[Air Cal\u00e9donie]]. Retrieved on 2 October 2009.</ref> Aircal's headquarters are on the grounds of [[Noum\u00e9a Magenta Airport]],<ref>\"[http://www.air-caledonie.nc/fr/pdf/carte_renew_nb.pdf Renouvellement de Carte R\u00e9sident] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090530002353/http://www.air-caledonie.nc/fr/pdf/carte_renew_nb.pdf |date=30 May 2009 }}.\" Air Cal\u00e9donie. Retrieved on 8 October 2009.</ref>\nwhich serves local routes. Noum\u00e9a's international airport is [[La Tontouta International Airport]], {{convert|50|km|mi}} from the city.\n\nThe [[Noum\u00e9a-Pa\u00efta railway]], which was the only railway line that ever existed in New Caledonia, was closed in 1940.\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Main building at Nouville campus, University of New Caledonia.png|thumb|250px|[[University of New Caledonia]], Nouville campus]]\n[[File:Exterior view of Bernheim Library, Noum\u00e9a.png|thumb|250px|Bernheim Library exterior]]\n[[File:Interior View 2 of Bernheim Library, Noumea.png|thumb|250px|Bernheim Library interior]]\nThe [[University of New Caledonia]]  (UNC) goes back to 1987 when the Universit\u00e9 Fran\u00e7aise du Pacifique (French University of the Pacific) was created, with two centres, one in French Polynesia and the other in New Caledonia. In 1997 the decision was made to split the two parts into separate universities and so in 1999 the Universit\u00e9 de la Nouvelle Cal\u00e9donie and the Universit\u00e9 de la Polyn\u00e9sie Fran\u00e7aise were formed.\n\nUNC welcomes around 3,000 local and international students and 100 professors and researchers each year.<ref>\"{{cite web |url=http://www.univ-nc.nc/propos-de-lunc/presentation |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-01-05 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119221009/http://www.univ-nc.nc/propos-de-lunc/presentation |archivedate=19 January 2012 |df=dmy-all }} Universit\u00e9 de la Nouvelle-Cal\u00e9donie. Retrieved on 5 January 2012.</ref>\n\nThe ''Biblioth\u00e8que Bernheim'' (Bernheim Library) is located in Noum\u00e9a.<ref>\"[http://www.bernheim.nc/distribution.asp?page=information/vico.asp&inter=0&num=5&parcours=information/paco.asp coordonn\u00e9es & horaires] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110316185105/http://www.bernheim.nc/distribution.asp?page=information%2Fvico.asp&inter=0&num=5&parcours=information%2Fpaco.asp |date=16 March 2011 }}.\" Biblioth\u00e8que Bernheim. Retrieved on 12 February 2011.</ref>\n\n==Twin towns \u2013 sister cities==\n*{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]] ([[Australia]])\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Nice]] ([[Metropolitan France|Metropolitan]] [[France]])<ref name=\"Nice Jumellage\">{{cite web | url = http://www.nice.fr/Collectivites/La-municipalite/Villes-jumelees-avec-la-Ville-de-Nice | title = Villes jumel\u00e9es avec la Ville de Nice | accessdate = 2013-06-24 | publisher = Ville de Nice | language = French | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121029114949/http://nice.fr/Collectivites/La-municipalite/Villes-jumelees-avec-la-Ville-de-Nice | archivedate = 29 October 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|NZL}} [[Taupo]] ([[New Zealand]])\n\n==Popular culture==\n* New Caledonia was the favorite liberty port in the Pacific of the crew of the ''PT-73'' in the American television series ''[[McHale's Navy]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pro.imdb.com/title/tt0055689/trivia |title=IMDbPro |publisher=Pro.imdb.com |date= |accessdate=2017-11-06}}</ref>\n* Sydney-based author Nathan J. Roche set his 2014 novel ''The Noum\u00e9a Neurosis'', a satirical prose account of cycling, in and around Noum\u00e9a.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thethousands.com.au/sydney/read/nathan-j-roche-the-noumea-neurosis--2 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-01-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170108190232/http://thethousands.com.au/sydney/read/nathan-j-roche-the-noumea-neurosis--2 |archivedate=8 January 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Noum\u00e9a}}\n*{{Wikivoyage-inline}}\n*[http://www.newcaledoniatourism-south.com/ Tourism New Caledonia (South)]\n*{{in lang|fr}} {{Official website|/www.ville-noumea.nc|Noum\u00e9a's official municipal website}}\n*{{in lang|fr}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20050328065902/http://www.ac-noumea.nc/laperouse/site-hg/site/ Noum\u00e9a: Commune Fran\u00e7aise du Bout du Monde] \u2013 a school project on the geography and history of Noum\u00e9a\n\n{{Administrative divisions of New Caledonia}}\n{{List of Oceanian capitals by region}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2011}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Noumea}}\n[[Category:Noum\u00e9a| ]]\n[[Category:Capitals in Oceania]]\n[[Category:Communes of New Caledonia]]\n[[Category:Port cities in Oceania]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noum%C3%A9a"}
{"title_page": "Jean Ker, Countess of Roxburghe", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2019}}\n'''Jean Ker, Countess of Roxburghe''' (''n\u00e9e'' [[Drummond family|Drummond]]; c.1585\u20131643), was a [[Kingdom of Scotland|Scottish]] courtier, serving [[Anne of Denmark]] in Scotland and England.\n\n==Courtier and Governess==\nShe was born Jean Drummond, the daughter of [[Patrick Drummond, 3rd Lord Drummond]], and his first wife, Elizabeth Lindsay.\n\nJean was a gentlewoman in the household of [[Anne of Denmark]], described as her \"familiar servitrix\", and had care over the infant [[Charles I of England|Prince Charles]] at [[Dunfermline Palace]] in 1602.<ref>James Maidment, ''Letters to King James the Sixth from the Queen, Prince Henry, Prince Charles'' (Edinburgh, 1836), p. lxxxi.</ref> \n\nIn 1603, on the [[Union of the Crowns|accession of]] [[James VI and I|James VI of Scotland]] to the throne of [[Kingdom of England|England]] (as James I), she accompanied Anne of Denmark, to [[Stirling Castle]] to take custody of their son, the [[Henry Frederick, Prince of Wales|Prince Henry]], and then to [[London]]. In the years before her marriage, Anne of Denmark gave her gifts of her old clothes.<ref>Jemma Field, [https://www.euppublishing.com/doi/pdfplus/10.3366/cost.2017.0003 'The Wardrobe Goods of Anna of Denmark', ''Costume'', vol. 51 no. 1 (March, 2017), p. 21], & supplement pp. 30, 37, 43.</ref>\n\nIn 1607/08, a marriage was arranged between her and [[Archibald Campbell, 7th Earl of Argyll]], but amounted to nothing. \n\nIn June 1609 Drummond and Lady Fleetwood stayed at the bedside of her kinsman and servant of the queen [[Alexander Drummond of Carnock|David Abercromby]] who was dying and he declared his will to them.<ref>Will of David Abercromby, TNA PROB 11/116/69.</ref> [[Cecily Bulstrode]] and [[Bridget Markham]], two of the queen's ladies in waiting, also died in the summer of 1609. At the end of November 1610 one of Drummond's maids died from the plague in her lodgings at [[Greenwich Palace]] and the queen returned to [[Whitehall]] for fear of infection.<ref>''HMC Rutland'' (London, 1905), p. 211.</ref>\n\nDrummond held a position of responsibility in the queen's household, and signed financial documents, including in 1612 a warrant for lifetime payments to the queen's four French musicians, the lutenists; Louis Richart, Camille Prevost, Claude Olivier, and Peter de la Mere.<ref>''HMC 2nd Report: Bromley-Davenport'' (London, 1874), p. 79.</ref>\n\nAs a close companion of the queen, Jean Drummond was able to intercede with her for the benefit of others. [[Arbella Stuart]] wrote to her with thanks for the queen's favour and hearing her suit, which Drummond had presented to the queen in a good light, and hoped that Jean would move the queen to ensure the king would \"weigh my cause aright\". Stuart sent Drummond, who was [[Mistress of the Robes]], gloves which she had embroidered herself, to be given to the queen.<ref>Sara Jayne Steen, ''The Letters of Lady Arbella Stuart'' (Oxford, 1994), pp. 244-6.</ref> Spanish diplomats also saw Jean Drummond as a route to influence the queen, and she was recommended by the ambassador [[Juan de Tassis, 1st Count of Villamediana|Juan de Tassis]] and received a Spanish pension.<ref>Cynthia Fry, 'Perceptions of Influences', in Nadine Akkerman, ''The Politics of Female Households'' (Brill: Leiden, 2014), pp. 281-84, see also fn. 72 listing some of Jean Drummond's letters.</ref> In 1611 the Spanish ambassador Alonso de Velasco wrote that a Catholic priest was concealed at the court of Anne of Denmark, posing as Drummond's servant.<ref>Jemma Field, 'Anna of Denmark and the Politics of Religious Identity' in ''Northern Studies'', vol. 50 (2019), pp. 98-9, 102, 107.</ref>\n\nShe married [[Robert Ker, 1st Earl of Roxburghe|Robert Ker, 1st Lord Roxburghe]] (later created [[Earl of Roxburghe]]), on 3 February 1614; the wedding was celebrated at [[Somerset House]] and attended by the king and queen. There was a masque ''Hymen's Triumph'' written by [[Samuel Daniel]].<ref>Martin Wiggins and Catherine Richardson, ''British Drama, 1533-1642'', vol. 6, 1609-1616, (Oxford, 2015), pp. 394-6.</ref> [[John Chamberlain (letter writer)|John Chamberlain]] heard that the queen would pay for the festivities, but no more than \u00a3500 for a marriage bed because \"her maid Drummond is rich enough otherwise, as well in wealth as in virtue and favour.\"<ref>Thomas Birch ed. Folkestone Williams, ''Court and Times of James the First'', vol. 1 (London, 1848), p. 279.</ref>\n\nAn Italian poet at the court of Denmark, Antonio Galli or Gatti wrote sonnets in her praise.<ref>[[William Drummond, 1st Viscount Strathallan|William Drummond]], [https://archive.org/details/genealogyofmostd00drum/page/254 ''The genealogy of the most noble and ancient House of Drummond'' (Glasgow, 1879), p. 254], citing notes made by [[Robert Mylne (writer)|Robert Mylne]] now [[National Library of Scotland]] Adv. MS.34.6.9.</ref>\n\nAfter her marriage she continued to sign letters as \"Jane Drummond\".<ref>''HMC Laing Manuscripts at Edinburgh University'', vol. 1 (London, 1914), p. 186.</ref>\n\nShe was with the queen during her illness at [[Greenwich Palace]] in May 1615. She wrote to her husband on 10 May 1615 that he was to thank the king for the letter, and that the physician [[Theodore de Mayerne]] was writing to the king with details of the queen's sickness. Anne's foot was swollen and she had been sitting a chair all day long.<ref>[[William Drummond, 1st Viscount Strathallan|William Drummond]],[https://archive.org/details/genealogyofmostd00drum/page/280 ''The genealogy of the most noble and ancient House of Drummond'' (Glasgow, 1879), p. 280, misdated], now held by the [[National Library of Scotland]].</ref>\n\nIn July 1615 she was bought a white gelding horse for \u00a316-10s in place of her old grey horse which was blind and lame. In March 1616 King James gave her \u00a33000 in recognition of her long service to the queen.<ref>Frederick Madden, ''Issues of the Exchequer'' (London, 1836), pp. 200, 319.</ref> In January 1617 she was godmother to Elizabeth Gordon, daughter of [[Sir Robert Gordon, 1st Baronet|Sir Robert Gordon of Gordonstoun]] and Louisa Gordon whose mother [[Genevi\u00e8ve Petau de Maulette]] is said to have taught French to Elizabeth of Bohemia. The other godparents were the [[Edward Seymour, 1st Earl of Hertford|Earl of Hertford]] and [[Lucy Russell, Countess of Bedford]].<ref>Robert Gordon, ''Genealogical history of the Earldom of Sutherland'' (Edinburgh, 1813), p. 343.</ref>\n\nIn 1617, Queen Anne forced the countess to retire from court after it was discovered that her husband sought to be appointed [[Lord Chamberlain]] to Prince Charles (later Charles I), without either of them informing the queen. Her dismissal particularly alarmed the [[ambassador]]s of [[Spain]] and [[Republic of Venice|Venice]], who had relied on the [[Roman Catholicism|Catholic]] countess as a confidante to the queen.\n\n==In Scotland==\nAn account of her and her husband's expenses from 1619 to 1630 runs to 550 pages, and mentions her residence at East Roxburgh, a townhouse in Edinburgh's Canongate, and [[Broxburn, East Lothian|Broxmouth]] near [[Dunbar]]. Food seasonings such as cinnamon, mace, ginger, and sugar almonds were bought in Edinburgh and sent to East Roxburgh, as were materials and ribbons for clothing. On 21 July 1619 she gave six shillings to a boy walking on stilts on [[Soutra Aisle|Soutra Hill]] who said he was going all the way to London.<ref>''HMC MSS of the Duke of Roxburghe etc'' (London, 1894), pp. 47-8.</ref>\n\nIn a letter of May 1622 she mentions her fear of sailing across the [[River Forth]] from [[Leith]], which she had never done before, to attend a christening in [[Fife, Scotland|Fife]].<ref>Lord Lindsay, ''Lives of the Lindsays'', vol. 2 (London, 1849), p. 408.</ref> However, an earlier journey to [[Dudhope Castle]] in 1619 involving crossing the Forth is detailed in the account book. In July 1623 she travelled with the [[John Maitland, 1st Earl of Lauderdale|Viscount Lauderdale]] to [[Drummond Castle]] in [[Strathearn]] to stay for a month with her brother [[John Drummond, 2nd Earl of Perth]].<ref>''The Melros Papers'', vol. 2 (Edinburgh, 1837), p. 525.</ref>\n\n==Royal Governess Again==\n\nIn 1630, the by-now Charles I had wished to appoint the countess as governess to his son, the [[Charles II of England|Prince of Wales]] (later Charles II) but this was objected to on the grounds of her religion and the [[Mary Sackville, Countess of Dorset|Countess of Dorset]] was appointed instead. A year later however, Lady Roxburghe was appointed governess to [[Mary, Princess Royal and Princess of Orange|Princess Mary]] and later to [[Henry Stuart, Duke of Gloucester|Prince Henry]] and [[Princess Elizabeth of England|Princess Elizabeth]] in 1641.\n\nIn 1642, the countess accompanied Princess Mary to [[The Hague]] after the latter's marriage to [[William II, Prince of Orange|Prince William of Orange]].<ref>Edinburgh University Centre for Research Collections has her letter to the Prince of Orange, 7 July 1642, see ''HMC Laing Manuscripts'', vol. 1 (London, 1914), pp. 210-1.</ref> On the voyage back from the Netherlands a ship of the royal fleet sank in bad weather. A silk dress belonging to the countess was discovered in 2014 in the wreck off the Dutch island of [[Texel]].<ref>{{cite news|date=21 April 2016|title=400-year-old dress found in shipwreck sheds light on plot to pawn crown jewels|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/apr/21/400-year-old-dress-found-in-shipwreck-sheds-light-on-plot-to-pawn-crown-jewels |newspaper=The Guardian|location=London|access-date=21 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn her return to England, the countess was replaced as the governess to Mary Princess Royal by [[Katherine Stanhope, Countess of Chesterfield|Lady Stanhope]]. She resumed her governess-ship to Henry and Elizabeth in 1642, and hosted Lilias Drummond, a daughter of the [[John Drummond, 2nd Earl of Perth|Earl of Perth]], at her house in London, who married [[James Murray, 2nd Earl of Tullibardine]] in May 1643.<ref>Joseph Foster, ''London marriage licences, 1521-1869'' (London, 1887), p. 954.</ref> The older sister of Lilias, also Jean Drummond, and later [[Earl of Wigtown|Countess of Wigtown]], was a nurse to royal children, as was another Jean Drummond, the widow of [[Thomas Murray (provost of Eton)|Secretary Murray]] and mother of [[Anne Halkett|Anne, Lady Halkett]].<ref>[[William Drummond, 1st Viscount Strathallan|William Drummond]], [https://archive.org/details/genealogyofmostd00drum/page/116 ''The genealogy of the most noble and ancient House of Drummond'' (Glasgow, 1879), pp. 116, 196, 209-210, 212:] ''The Autobiography of Anne Murray, Lady Halkett'', p. 1.</ref>\n\nShe died on 7 October 1643 and was buried in [[Holyrood Abbey]].\n\n==Family==\nHer first son died in 1616. A daughter was christened at Greenwich in April 1616.<ref>Thomas Birch ed. Folkestone Williams, ''Court and Times of James the First'', vol. 1 (London, 1848), p. 402.</ref> A son Henry Kerr married Margaret Hay, a daughter of the [[Earl of Erroll]]. He died in 1643, leaving four daughters, Jean, Margaret, and Sophia (born after his death).<ref>''Correspondence of Sir Robert Kerr, first Earl of Ancram'', vol. 1 (Roxburghe Club: Edinburgh, 1875), p. 145-6.</ref>. Margaret Hay subsequently married the [[Earl of Cassilis]].\n\nHenry Kerr joined the supporters of the Scottish covenant who opposed the king. On 20 May 1639, Jean Roxburghe wrote from Whitehall to [[Walter Balcanquhall]], Dean of Durham, expressing her disappointment over this defection.<ref>''Letters and Journals of Robert Baillie'', vol. 2 (Edinburgh, 1841), pp. 435-6, from NLS Wodrow MS LXVI no. 23.</ref>\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/70617 Payne, Helen - ''Ker/Kerr; n\u00e9e Drummond, Jane/Jean, countess of Roxburghe (b. in or before 1585, d. 1643), courtier''] - ''[[ODNB]]''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roxburghe, Jean Ker, Countess of}}\n[[Category:1580s births]]\n[[Category:1643 deaths]]\n[[Category:Daughters of barons]]\n[[Category:Drummond family|Jean]]\n[[Category:Scottish governesses]]\n[[Category:Ladies of the Bedchamber]]\n[[Category:Scottish ladies-in-waiting]]\n[[Category:Scottish countesses]]\n[[Category:Scottish Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Women of the Stuart period]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n[[Category:17th-century Scottish educators]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish women]]\n[[Category:17th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:17th-century Scottish women]]\n[[Category:Court of James VI and I]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2019}}\n'''Jean Ker, Countess of Roxburghe''' (''n\u00e9e'' [[Drummond family|Drummond]]; c.1585\u20131643), was a [[Kingdom of Scotland|Scottish]] courtier, serving [[Anne of Denmark]] in Scotland and England.\n\n==Courtier and Governess==\nShe was born Jean Drummond, the daughter of [[Patrick Drummond, 3rd Lord Drummond]], and his first wife, Elizabeth Lindsay.\n\nJean was a gentlewoman in the household of [[Anne of Denmark]], described as her \"familiar servitrix\", and had care over the infant [[Charles I of England|Prince Charles]] at [[Dunfermline Palace]] in 1602.<ref>James Maidment, ''Letters to King James the Sixth from the Queen, Prince Henry, Prince Charles'' (Edinburgh, 1836), p. lxxxi.</ref> \n\nIn 1603, on the [[Union of the Crowns|accession of]] [[James VI and I|James VI of Scotland]] to the throne of [[Kingdom of England|England]] (as James I), she accompanied Anne of Denmark, to [[Stirling Castle]] to take custody of their son, the [[Henry Frederick, Prince of Wales|Prince Henry]], and then to [[London]]. In the years before her marriage, Anne of Denmark gave her gifts of her old clothes.<ref>Jemma Field, [https://www.euppublishin