eived a Spanish pension.<ref>Cynthia Fry, 'Perceptions of Influences', in Nadine Akkerman, ''The Politics of Female Households'' (Brill: Leiden, 2014), pp. 281-84, see also fn. 72 listing some of Jean Drummond's letters.</ref> In 1611 the Spanish ambassador Alonso de Velasco wrote that a Catholic priest was concealed at the court of Anne of Denmark, posing as Drummond's servant.<ref>Jemma Field, 'Anna of Denmark and the Politics of Religious Identity' in ''Northern Studies'', vol. 50 (2019), pp. 98-9, 102, 107.</ref>\n\nShe married [[Robert Ker, 1st Earl of Roxburghe|Robert Ker, 1st Lord Roxburghe]] (later created [[Earl of Roxburghe]]), on 3 February 1614; the wedding was celebrated at [[Somerset House]] and attended by the king and queen. There was a masque ''Hymen's Triumph'' written by [[Samuel Daniel]].<ref>Martin Wiggins and Catherine Richardson, ''British Drama, 1533-1642'', vol. 6, 1609-1616, (Oxford, 2015), pp. 394-6.</ref> [[John Chamberlain (letter writer)|John Chamberlain]] heard that the queen would pay for the festivities, but no more than \u00a3500 for a marriage bed because \"her maid Drummond is rich enough otherwise, as well in wealth as in virtue and favour.\"<ref>Thomas Birch ed. Folkestone Williams, ''Court and Times of James the First'', vol. 1 (London, 1848), p. 279.</ref>\n\nAn Italian poet at the court of Denmark, Antonio Galli or Gatti wrote sonnets in her praise.<ref>[[William Drummond, 1st Viscount Strathallan|William Drummond]], [https://archive.org/details/genealogyofmostd00drum/page/254 ''The genealogy of the most noble and ancient House of Drummond'' (Glasgow, 1879), p. 254], citing notes made by [[Robert Mylne (writer)|Robert Mylne]] now [[National Library of Scotland]] Adv. MS.34.6.9.</ref>\n\nAfter her marriage she continued to sign letters as \"Jane Drummond\".<ref>''HMC Laing Manuscripts at Edinburgh University'', vol. 1 (London, 1914), p. 186.</ref>\n\nShe was with the queen during her illness at [[Greenwich Palace]] in May 1615. She wrote to her husband on 10 May 1615 that he was to thank the king for the letter, and that the physician [[Theodore de Mayerne]] was writing to the king with details of the queen's sickness. Anne's foot was swollen and she had been sitting a chair all day long.<ref>[[William Drummond, 1st Viscount Strathallan|William Drummond]],[https://archive.org/details/genealogyofmostd00drum/page/280 ''The genealogy of the most noble and ancient House of Drummond'' (Glasgow, 1879), p. 280, misdated], now held by the [[National Library of Scotland]].</ref>\n\nIn July 1615 she was bought a white gelding horse for \u00a316-10s in place of her old grey horse which was blind and lame. In March 1616 King James gave her \u00a33000 in recognition of her long service to the queen.<ref>Frederick Madden, ''Issues of the Exchequer'' (London, 1836), pp. 200, 319.</ref>\n\nIn 1617, Queen Anne forced the countess to retire from court after it was discovered that her husband sought to be appointed [[Lord Chamberlain]] to Prince Charles (later Charles I), without either of them informing the queen. Her dismissal particularly alarmed the [[ambassador]]s of [[Spain]] and [[Republic of Venice|Venice]], who had relied on the [[Roman Catholicism|Catholic]] countess as a confidante to the queen.\n\n==In Scotland==\nAn account of her and her husband's expenses from 1619 to 1630 runs to 550 pages, and mentions her residence at East Roxburgh, a townhouse in Edinburgh's Canongate, and [[Broxburn, East Lothian|Broxmouth]] near [[Dunbar]]. Food seasonings such as cinnamon, mace, ginger, and sugar almonds were bought in Edinburgh and sent to East Roxburgh, as were materials and ribbons for clothing. On 21 July 1619 she gave six shillings to a boy walking on stilts on [[Soutra Aisle|Soutra Hill]] who said he was going all the way to London.<ref>''HMC MSS of the Duke of Roxburghe etc'' (London, 1894), pp. 47-8.</ref>\n\nIn a letter of May 1622 she mentions her fear of sailing across the [[River Forth]] from [[Leith]], which she had never done before, to attend a christening in [[Fife, Scotland|Fife]].<ref>Lord Lindsay, ''Lives of the Lindsays'', vol. 2 (London, 1849), p. 408.</ref> However, an earlier journey to [[Dudhope Castle]] in 1619 involving crossing the Forth is detailed in the account book. In July 1623 she travelled with the [[John Maitland, 1st Earl of Lauderdale|Viscount Lauderdale]] to [[Drummond Castle]] in [[Strathearn]] to stay for a month with her brother [[John Drummond, 2nd Earl of Perth]].<ref>''The Melros Papers'', vol. 2 (Edinburgh, 1837), p. 525.</ref>\n\n==Royal Governess Again==\n\nIn 1630, the by-now Charles I had wished to appoint the countess as governess to his son, the [[Charles II of England|Prince of Wales]] (later Charles II) but this was objected to on the grounds of her religion and the [[Mary Sackville, Countess of Dorset|Countess of Dorset]] was appointed instead. A year later however, Lady Roxburghe was appointed governess to [[Mary, Princess Royal and Princess of Orange|Princess Mary]] and later to [[Henry Stuart, Duke of Gloucester|Prince Henry]] and [[Princess Elizabeth of England|Princess Elizabeth]] in 1641.\n\nIn 1642, the countess accompanied Princess Mary to [[The Hague]] after the latter's marriage to [[William II, Prince of Orange|Prince William of Orange]].<ref>Edinburgh University Centre for Research Collections has her letter to the Prince of Orange, 7 July 1642, see ''HMC Laing Manuscripts'', vol. 1 (London, 1914), pp. 210-1.</ref> On the voyage back from the Netherlands a ship of the royal fleet sank in bad weather. A silk dress belonging to the countess was discovered in 2014 in the wreck off the Dutch island of [[Texel]].<ref>{{cite news|date=21 April 2016|title=400-year-old dress found in shipwreck sheds light on plot to pawn crown jewels|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/apr/21/400-year-old-dress-found-in-shipwreck-sheds-light-on-plot-to-pawn-crown-jewels |newspaper=The Guardian|location=London|access-date=21 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn her return to England, the countess was replaced as the governess to Mary Princess Royal by [[Katherine Stanhope, Countess of Chesterfield|Lady Stanhope]]. She resumed her governess-ship to Henry and Elizabeth in 1642, and hosted Lilias Drummond, a daughter of the [[John Drummond, 2nd Earl of Perth|Earl of Perth]], at her house in London, who married [[James Murray, 2nd Earl of Tullibardine]] in May 1643.<ref>Joseph Foster, ''London marriage licences, 1521-1869'' (London, 1887), p. 954.</ref> The older sister of Lilias, also Jean Drummond, and later [[Earl of Wigtown|Countess of Wigtown]], was a nurse to royal children, as was another Jean Drummond, the widow of [[Thomas Murray (provost of Eton)|Secretary Murray]] and mother of [[Anne Halkett|Anne, Lady Halkett]].<ref>[[William Drummond, 1st Viscount Strathallan|William Drummond]], [https://archive.org/details/genealogyofmostd00drum/page/116 ''The genealogy of the most noble and ancient House of Drummond'' (Glasgow, 1879), pp. 116, 196, 209-210, 212:] ''The Autobiography of Anne Murray, Lady Halkett'', p. 1.</ref>\n\nShe died on 7 October 1643 and was buried in [[Holyrood Abbey]].\n\n==Family==\nHer first son died in 1616. A daughter was christened at Greenwich in April 1616.<ref>Thomas Birch ed. Folkestone Williams, ''Court and Times of James the First'', vol. 1 (London, 1848), p. 402.</ref> A son Henry Kerr married Margaret Hay, a daughter of the [[Earl of Erroll]]. He died in 1643, leaving four daughters, Jean, Margaret, and Sophia (born after his death).<ref>''Correspondence of Sir Robert Kerr, first Earl of Ancram'', vol. 1 (Roxburghe Club: Edinburgh, 1875), p. 145-6.</ref>. Margaret Hay subsequently married the [[Earl of Cassilis]].\n\nHenry Kerr joined the supporters of the Scottish covenant who opposed the king. On 20 May 1639, Jean Roxburghe wrote from Whitehall to [[Walter Balcanquhall]], Dean of Durham, expressing her disappointment over this defection.<ref>''Letters and Journals of Robert Baillie'', vol. 2 (Edinburgh, 1841), pp. 435-6, from NLS Wodrow MS LXVI no. 23.</ref>\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/70617 Payne, Helen - ''Ker/Kerr; n\u00e9e Drummond, Jane/Jean, countess of Roxburghe (b. in or before 1585, d. 1643), courtier''] - ''[[ODNB]]''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roxburghe, Jean Ker, Countess of}}\n[[Category:1580s births]]\n[[Category:1643 deaths]]\n[[Category:Daughters of barons]]\n[[Category:Drummond family|Jean]]\n[[Category:Scottish governesses]]\n[[Category:Ladies of the Bedchamber]]\n[[Category:Scottish ladies-in-waiting]]\n[[Category:Scottish countesses]]\n[[Category:Scottish Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Women of the Stuart period]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n[[Category:17th-century Scottish educators]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish women]]\n[[Category:17th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:17th-century Scottish women]]\n[[Category:Court of James VI and I]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "1617", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean_Ker,_Countess_of_Roxburghe"}
{"title_page": "The Mad Pooper", "text_new": "{{Short description|Unidentified woman who regularly defecated in a Colorado family's yard during summer 2017}}\n{{coord|38.96755|-104.76738|display=title}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name = The Mad Pooper\n| image = The Mad Pooper.JPG\n| image_upright = \n| image_size = 140\n| alt = A woman with short brown hair in running motion, wearing a gray tank top and darker gray tight-fitting shorts and neon blue and green running shoes. She is on a sidewalk with a cream-colored wooden fence behind her\n| caption = An image of the suspected Mad Pooper, captured by Cathy Budde on her cell phone\n| years_active = 2017\n| known_for = Repeatedly defecating in public while jogging\n| criminal_charge = [[Public urination|Public defecation]], [[indecent exposure in the United States|indecent exposure]]\n| capture_status = At large and unidentified\n| wanted_by = [[Colorado Springs Police Department]]\n| partners = \n| wanted_since = July 2017\n}}\n'''The Mad Pooper''' is the nickname given to an unidentified woman in [[Colorado Springs, Colorado]], United States, who repeatedly [[open defecation|defecated in public]] while jogging during the summer months of 2017. While she has primarily targeted one family's property, she has not used it exclusively, leaving some of [[human feces|her excrement]] at other sites nearby. Photographs of her have been made public, but neither she nor anyone who knows her has come forward with further information that might identify her.<ref name=\"Washington Post story\">{{cite news|last=Chason|first=Rachel|title=Colorado Springs police seek runner who won't stop pooping in front of a family\u2019s house|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2017/09/19/this-runner-wont-stop-pooping-in-front-of-a-familys-house-now-shes-being-sought-by-police/|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=September 19, 2017|accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\nPolice believe the woman's actions are intentional, since there are several [[public toilet]]s within a [[city block|block]] of the family's house that she could use. After the case received national media attention, a purported spokesman claimed in a [[YouTube]] video that her actions were related to recent medical issues and enjoyed [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] protection;<ref name=\"Fox News spokesperson story\">{{cite news|title=Colorado's 'Mad Pooper' sorry, spokesman says|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2017/09/26/mad-poopers-spokesman-tries-to-clear-air.html|newspaper=[[Fox News]]|date=September 26, 2017|accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref> however that video turned out to be a hoax. [[Procter & Gamble]] has offered her a free year's supply of its [[Charmin]] brand toilet paper if she turns herself in.<ref name=\"P&G tweet\">{{cite web|author=[[Procter & Gamble]]|title=If the #MadPooper turns herself in, we'll give her a year's supply of TP to help with her \"runs\" \ud83d\udca9 #EnjoyTheGo|url=https://twitter.com/Charmin/status/910616027721076736|publisher=[[Twitter]]|date=September 20, 2017|accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter a burst of news media coverage in mid-September, police reported that there had been no further reports of the woman defecating in public, although she had not been identified. A few commentators speculated about her possible motives. One believed she might suffer from [[Crohn's disease]]; another, in ''[[Psychology Today]]'', proposed that she was an [[exhibitionism|exhibitionist]] with [[impulse control disorder|poor impulse control]] who was taking revenge on the family that had caught her.\n\n==History==\n\nCathy Budde says the defecations began in mid-July 2017, outside their house near the intersection of Briargate Boulevard and North Union Parkway in the northern end of [[Colorado Springs, Colorado]].<ref name=\"KKTV story\">{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Spencer|title='Mad Pooper' wanted by Springs police|url=http://www.kktv.com/content/news/Mad-Pooper-wanted-by-Springs-Police-444969443.html|newspaper=[[KKTV]]|date=September 16, 2017|accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref> As she later told local TV station [[KKTV]], her children came in one day and told her \"There's a lady taking a poop!\"<ref name=\"Washington Post story\" />\n\nBudde was not sure they were serious, and went outside to see for herself. There she saw the woman, squatting, with her jogging shorts around her ankles. When Budde confronted the woman about having [[open defecation|defecated in public]] and allowing the Budde children to see her private parts in the process, the woman said \"Yeah ... sorry\" and left after pulling up her shorts. Budde assumed she would return quickly to clean up the feces, and never again jog in the area due to the embarrassment the incident caused.<ref name=\"Washington Post story\" />\n\nInstead, the Buddes found feces at the same spot on the sidewalk at least once a week.{{efn|A similar incident occurred in [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]], in 2013. [[Security camera]]s outside a home in that city's [[Nob Hill, Albuquerque, New Mexico|Nob Hill]] neighborhood repeatedly caught the same woman jogging past and defecating on weekend mornings. She, too, was never identified.<ref name=\"KOAT 2013 story\">{{cite news|last=Colorado|first=Melissa|title=She did what?!? Runner caught pooping in yard|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3tD4nmw1yZs|newspaper=[[KOAT-TV]]|via=[[YouTube]]|date=July 17, 2013|accessdate=November 5, 2017}}</ref>}} Paper napkins and wipes the jogger had used to clean herself were often nearby. On three occasions Budde saw the woman defecate.<ref name=\"Washington Post story\" /> The Budde children began calling her \"The Mad Pooper of Pine Creek\" after a stream that flows through the neighborhood, sometimes used as its name.<ref name=\"KKTV story\" />\n\n\"This is intentional\", Budde told ''[[The Washington Post]]''. There are, she explained, several [[public toilet]]s nearby the woman could use. There is one across the street, [[portable toilet]]s in a nearby public park, and some at a gas station a short distance away. All would be easy for the jogger to use if she regularly had the need while running. Neighbors also told Budde they had seen the woman defecating in their back yards as well as near a local [[Walgreens]] drugstore.<ref name=\"Washington Post story\" />\n\nBudde notified the [[Colorado Springs Police Department]] (CSPD), and made attempts on her own to end the jogger's defecations. She took pictures from the house, capturing a short brown-haired woman in a gray tank top and shorts. She put up a printed paper sign at the place near her house favored by the jogger, warning her that the police were aware of the situation, and asking her to stop.<ref name=\"Washington Post story\" />\n\nIn response, Budde said, the woman began changing the times she jogged by. She also ignored the note's pleas, running by it 15 times in one day before defecating near it again, according to Budde. The police have said she could face charges of [[Indecent exposure in the United States|indecent exposure]] and [[public defecation]] were they to identify and arrest her,<ref name=\"Washington Post story\" /> charges that, in the event of a conviction, might require that she [[Sex offender registries in the United States|register as a sex offender]].<ref name=\"KRDO spokesman story\">{{cite news|last=Clemens|first=Dana|title=Attorneys discuss rights to pooping in public after \"Mad Pooper\" video release|url=http://www.krdo.com/news/colorado-springs/mad-pooper-spokesman-explains/626058098|newspaper=[[KRDO-TV]]|date=September 27, 2017|accessdate=November 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOne officer, Lt. Howard Black, said he had never seen anything similar in his 35-year career in Colorado Springs. Like Budde, he admitted to the ''Post'' that it was amusing, but allowed for the possibility that the jogger might not be in full control of her actions. \"If it's a mental health issue, she'll still be held accountable, but we would want to get her help.\"<ref name=\"Washington Post story\" />\n\nIn September, almost two months after the jogger's defecations had begun, Budde went to KKTV, which reported on the story. Shortly afterwards, the ''Post'' wrote its article, and the story [[Viral phenomenon|went viral]].<ref name=\"Fox News October story\">{{cite news|title='Mad Pooper' inquiries should stop now, Colorado police say|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2017/10/04/mad-pooper-inquiries-should-stop-now-colorado-police-say.html|newspaper=[[Fox News]]|date=October 4, 2017|accessdate=November 1, 2017}}</ref> Through its [[Twitter]] account, [[Procter & Gamble]] made an offer to the jogger: if she turned herself in to police, they would give her a year's supply of the company's [[Charmin]] toilet paper for free.<ref name=\"P&G tweet\" />\n\n''[[Runner's World]]'' magazine ran a story with a headline asking the woman to stop. \"[A]s runners, we understand having a sudden emergency now and then. But when it becomes a habit, you need to change up your regimen.\" it wrote, giving readers the phone number for the CSPD to call if they believed they knew who the Mad Pooper was. The article further urged readers who might similarly be using public places to defecate on their runs to likewise stop. \"Pull up your pants, and take your business elsewhere. We do not know what else to say.\"<ref name=\"Runner's World editorial\">{{cite news|title=We Urge You 'Mad Pooper,' Stop Crapping in Your Neighbor's Yard|url=https://www.runnersworld.com/poop/we-urge-you-mad-pooper-stop-crapping-in-your-neighbors-yard|newspaper=[[Runner's World]]|date=September 19, 2017|accessdate=November 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSports news website ''[[Deadspin]]'' called the CSPD about the case so frequently the department asked them to stop in early October since they had nothing new to report.<ref name=\"Deadspin October story\">{{cite news|last=Redford|first=Patrick|title=Colorado Springs Police Beg Us To Stop Calling About The Mad Pooper, Who Is Still At Large|url=https://deadspin.com/colorado-springs-police-beg-us-to-stop-calling-about-th-1819084370|newspaper=[[Deadspin]]|date=October 3, 2017|accessdate=November 1, 2017}}</ref> Since then, police report, the woman appears to have stopped. However, despite the increase in publicity around the case the woman has not been identified.<ref name=\"Fox News October story\" />\n\n===Hoax spokesman===\n\nIn response to the news coverage, a video was posted on [[YouTube]] by someone who claimed to be a family member of the jogger, who he called \"Shirley\". He said she was sorry for repeatedly fouling the Buddes' yard. However he also attributed her inability to control herself to a [[traumatic brain injury]] and complications from recent [[Sex reassignment surgery (male-to-female)|sex reassignment surgery]].<ref name=\"KRDO spokesman story\" />\n\nBeyond that, however, he said it was irrelevant as she was not breaking any law. Her actions, he argued, were protected under the [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]], much like [[breastfeeding]]. Jeremy Loew, a criminal defense attorney consulted by Colorado Springs television station [[KRDO-TV]] emphatically rejected that claim. If the video truly was posted by \"Shirley\"'s family, Loew said, it was \"actually the worst thing the[y] could do. ... Maybe they thought the videos would make the situation go away, but they won't.\" The spokesman might even find himself called as a witness, Loew added.<ref name=\"KRDO spokesman story\" />\n\nA few days later, the man posted a second video in which he disclosed that the first one was a hoax.<ref name=\"Thrillist videos post\">{{cite news|last=Blum|first=Sam|title=The Mad Pooper Is Sorry For Repeatedly Pooping on Colorado Family's Lawn|url=https://www.thrillist.com/news/nation/mad-pooper-colorado-jogger-apologizes-for-pooping-on-familys-lawn|newspaper=[[Thrillist]]|date=September 30, 2017|accessdate=November 3, 2017}}</ref> He was later revealed to be DISOP TV, another YouTube user known for producing videos of flatulent pets, who admitted he made up the first video as \"satire.\" Both that video and the original were soon deleted from the site.<ref name=\"Deadspin October story\" />\n\n==Possible motives==\n\nSome news outlets went beyond reporting on the case to speculate as to what the reasons for the jogger's actions might be. Allison Feller, a writer for ''[[Women's Health (magazine)|Women's Health]]'', wondered if, like her, the Mad Pooper might be an avid runner who suffers from [[Crohn's disease]], a bowel inflammation whose symptoms can sometimes include an [[Fecal incontinence|inability to hold excrement long enough to reach a toilet]]. \"[M]y first thought upon seeing this headline\" she recalled, \"was, 'Oh my god, being the subject of this story is my greatest fear.'\"<ref name=\"Women's Health story\">{{cite news|last=Feller|first=Allison|title=Why I'm Not Laughing At That Viral Story About A Jogger Dubbed 'The Mad Pooper'|url=https://www.womenshealthmag.com/health/pooping-runner-mad-pooper|newspaper=[[Women's Health (magazine)|Women's Health]]|date=September 20, 2017|accessdate=November 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSometimes her disease left her in such pain as to be unable to run or even leave the house, Feller wrote. But when it did, she would experience symptoms very suddenly. \"[Crohn's] can strike when you least expect it. And when that happens, my intestines go from totally chill to totally explosive faster than you can even ''think'' about where the closest available restroom may be.\"<ref name=\"Women's Health story\" />\n\nFeller said she, too, took toilet paper and wipes with her every time she went for a run. \"I don't run with these things because I'm ''planning'' to use them. I run with them because I've learned to be prepared.\" She recounted many times when, due to public bathrooms being closed or too distant for her to reach she had had to seclude herself behind trees or under bridges in order to defecate. One time, she admitted, she had even had to use her pants.<ref name=\"Women's Health story\" />\n\n\"In an age where everyone is armed with a cell-phone camera, I am terrified of someone seeing me going to the bathroom in an unapproved place, then snapping a photo or video, and posting it for the world to see, LOL at, and comment on\", Feller wrote. She felt considerable shame over the way her disease inconvenienced her, and called the idea of experiencing [[public shaming]] on the Internet because of it \"paralyzing\". She warned readers who might not understand that feeling that they should not shame someone they see experiencing similar distress while running. \"[O]ne day, you, too, may eat a burrito that doesn't agree with your stomach, and you may find yourself in a non-bathroom bathroom situation.<ref name=\"Women's Health story\" />\n\nAt ''[[Psychology Today]]'', Dale Hartley, an associate professor of psychology at [[West Virginia University at Parkersburg]], was dismissive of the idea that the Mad Pooper might suffer from an ailment that caused those problems, since she was so public in her defecations and had shown no sign of changing her routine to avoid having to do so. Nor did he think she had any [[psychosis]], as she was \"too put-together to be out of touch with reality\" and kept to a regular schedule. \"We would not expect to see consistently organized, predictable behaviors in someone who has undergone a psychotic break,\" Hartley wrote.<ref name=\"Psychology Today blog post\">{{cite news|last=Hartley|first=Dale|title=What's Up with the Mad Pooper of Colorado Springs?|url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/machiavellians-gulling-the-rubes/201709/whats-the-mad-pooper-colorado-springs|newspaper=[[Psychology Today]]|date=September 20, 2017|accessdate=November 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIt was more likely, Hartley presumed, that some lesser psychological issues led to her actions. \"Is she an [[exhibitionism|exhibitionist]]?  I think this is closer to the truth\", he wrote. But even if this was so, he believed, the jogger's real problem was [[impulse control disorder]].\n{{quote|When they bare it all, exhibitionists have failed to control their impulse to reveal too much. The mad pooper's abnormal impulse may or may not be exhibitionism. She might instead feel an overwhelming urge to experience the sensation of a bowel movement out in the open air. Or to flaunt{{sic}} social rules, break the law, and get away with it (the same kind of thrill that a [[kleptomania]]c gets). So whatever itch she's scratching, I'd put my money on an impulse control disorder as the milk in her magnesia.}}\nHer choice of the same location for so many of her defecations, Hartley also speculated, may have been retaliation against the Buddes for having caught her in the act.<ref name=\"Psychology Today blog post\" />\n\n==Other instances==\n===The Newcastle Star Jumper===\nAn instance was reported by the [[Newcastle Chronicle]] in the [[United Kingdom]] of a female jogger caught defecating on CCTV in the outskirts of [[Newcastle-upon-Tyne]].<ref name=\"Shopkeeper furious after CCTV captures moment jogger appears to defecate outside store\">{{cite news|last=Johnson|first=Ian|title=Shopkeeper furious after CCTV captures moment jogger appears to defecate outside store|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/shopkeeper-furious-after-cctv-captures-16780061|newspaper=[[Newcastle Chronicle]]|date=August 22, 2019|accessdate=August 22, 2019}}</ref> Nicknamed the \"Star Jumper\" due to her performing [[star jumps]] after the act, she has not been identified.\n\n===The Lincoln Pooper===\n[[1011now]] reported an unknown female in [[Lincoln, Nebraska]] who'd been caught on camera pooing outside a local swimming pool.<ref name=\"Woman caught defecating near local swimming pool\">{{cite news|last=1011now|first=|title=Woman caught defecating near local swimming pool|url=https://www.1011now.com/content/news/Woman-caught-defecating-near-local-swimming-pool-494011931.html|date=September 21, 2018|accessdate=September 21, 2018}}</ref>   Having been noted on multiple occasions to repeat the act before the pool opened and after it closed, at the time of the report she had yet to be identified.\n\n===The Brisbane Poo Jogger===\n[[News.com.au]] reported a male 64 year old male corporate executive nicknamed the \"Poo Jogger\" also caught on camera in [[Brisbane]], [[Australia]].<ref name=\"Doctors explain the possible reasons why people poo in public\">{{cite news|last=Brown|first=Vanessa|title=Doctors explain the possible reasons why people poo in public|url=https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/health-problems/psychologist-explains-the-possible-reasons-why-people-poo-in-public/news-story/46b58e6e5f6246323e9a75f52a6b470f|date=June 9, 2018|accessdate=June 9, 2018}}</ref> The suspect was caught after residents banded together after suspected multiple instances and photographed the culprit in the act.   Attracting worldwide interest, he was charged with creating a public nuisance.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Colorado|Law}}\n*[[2017 in the United States]]\n*[[Crime in Colorado]]\n*\"[[Broadcast Wagstaff School News]]\", a 2013 episode of the animated comedy series ''[[Bob's Burgers]]'' which featured an unidentified \"Mad Pooper\"\n*[[Runner's diarrhea]], which has led to runners defecating in public\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mad Pooper, The}}\n[[Category:Unidentified criminals]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Colorado]]\n[[Category:21st-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:American female criminals]]\n[[Category:Water supply and sanitation in the United States]]\n[[Category:Defecation]]\n[[Category:2017 in Colorado]]\n[[Category:2017 crimes in the United States]]\n[[Category:2010s in Colorado Springs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Unidentified woman who regularly defecated in a Colorado family's yard during summer 2017}}\n{{coord|38.96755|-104.76738|display=title}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name = The Mad Pooper\n| image = The Mad Pooper.JPG\n| image_upright = \n| image_size = 140\n| alt = A woman with short brown hair in running motion, wearing a gray tank top and darker gray tight-fitting shorts and neon blue and green running shoes. She is on a sidewalk with a cream-colored wooden fence behind her\n| caption = An image of the suspected Mad Pooper, captured by Cathy Budde on her cell phone\n| years_active = 2017\n| known_for = Repeatedly defecating in public while jogging\n| criminal_charge = [[Public urination|Public defecation]], [[indecent exposure in the United States|indecent exposure]]\n| capture_status = At large and unidentified\n| wanted_by = [[Colorado Springs Police Department]]\n| partners = \n| wanted_since = July 2017\n}}\n'''The Mad Pooper''' is the nickname given to an unidentified woman in [[Colorado Springs, Colorado]], United States, who repeatedly [[open defecation|defecated in public]] while jogging during the summer months of 2017. While she has primarily targeted one family's property, she has not used it exclusively, leaving some of [[human feces|her excrement]] at other sites nearby. Photographs of her have been made public, but neither she nor anyone who knows her has come forward with further information that might identify her.<ref name=\"Washington Post story\">{{cite news|last=Chason|first=Rachel|title=Colorado Springs police seek runner who won't stop pooping in front of a family\u2019s house|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2017/09/19/this-runner-wont-stop-pooping-in-front-of-a-familys-house-now-shes-being-sought-by-police/|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=September 19, 2017|accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\nPolice believe the woman's actions are intentional, since there are several [[public toilet]]s within a [[city block|block]] of the family's house that she could use. After the case received national media attention, a purported spokesman claimed in a [[YouTube]] video that her actions were related to recent medical issues and enjoyed [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] protection;<ref name=\"Fox News spokesperson story\">{{cite news|title=Colorado's 'Mad Pooper' sorry, spokesman says|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2017/09/26/mad-poopers-spokesman-tries-to-clear-air.html|newspaper=[[Fox News]]|date=September 26, 2017|accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref> however that video turned out to be a hoax. [[Procter & Gamble]] has offered her a free year's supply of its [[Charmin]] brand toilet paper if she turns herself in.<ref name=\"P&G tweet\">{{cite web|author=[[Procter & Gamble]]|title=If the #MadPooper turns herself in, we'll give her a year's supply of TP to help with her \"runs\" \ud83d\udca9 #EnjoyTheGo|url=https://twitter.com/Charmin/status/910616027721076736|publisher=[[Twitter]]|date=September 20, 2017|accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter a burst of news media coverage in mid-September, police reported that there had been no further reports of the woman defecating in public, although she had not been identified. A few commentators speculated about her possible motives. One believed she might suffer from [[Crohn's disease]]; another, in ''[[Psychology Today]]'', proposed that she was an [[exhibitionism|exhibitionist]] with [[impulse control disorder|poor impulse control]] who was taking revenge on the family that had caught her.\n\n==History==\n\nCathy Budde says the defecations began in mid-July 2017, outside their house near the intersection of Briargate Boulevard and North Union Parkway in the northern end of [[Colorado Springs, Colorado]].<ref name=\"KKTV story\">{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Spencer|title='Mad Pooper' wanted by Springs police|url=http://www.kktv.com/content/news/Mad-Pooper-wanted-by-Springs-Police-444969443.html|newspaper=[[KKTV]]|date=September 16, 2017|accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref> As she later told local TV station [[KKTV]], her children came in one day and told her \"There's a lady taking a poop!\"<ref name=\"Washington Post story\" />\n\nBudde was not sure they were serious, and went outside to see for herself. There she saw the woman, squatting, with her jogging shorts around her ankles. When Budde confronted the woman about having [[open defecation|defecated in public]] and allowing the Budde children to see her private parts in the process, the woman said \"Yeah ... sorry\" and left after pulling up her shorts. Budde assumed she would return quickly to clean up the feces, and never again jog in the area due to the embarrassment the incident caused.<ref name=\"Washington Post story\" />\n\nInstead, the Buddes found feces at the same spot on the sidewalk at least once a week.{{efn|A similar incident occurred in [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]], in 2013. [[Security camera]]s outside a home in that city's [[Nob Hill, Albuquerque, New Mexico|Nob Hill]] neighborhood repeatedly caught the same woman jogging past and defecating on weekend mornings. She, too, was never identified.<ref name=\"KOAT 2013 story\">{{cite news|last=Colorado|first=Melissa|title=She did what?!? Runner caught pooping in yard|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3tD4nmw1yZs|newspaper=[[KOAT-TV]]|via=[[YouTube]]|date=July 17, 2013|accessdate=November 5, 2017}}</ref>}} Paper napkins and wipes the jogger had used to clean herself were often nearby. On three occasions Budde saw the woman defecate.<ref name=\"Washington Post story\" /> The Budde children began calling her \"The Mad Pooper of Pine Creek\" after a stream that flows through the neighborhood, sometimes used as its name.<ref name=\"KKTV story\" />\n\n\"This is intentional\", Budde told ''[[The Washington Post]]''. There are, she explained, several [[public toilet]]s nearby the woman could use. There is one across the street, [[portable toilet]]s in a nearby public park, and some at a gas station a short distance away. All would be easy for the jogger to use if she regularly had the need while running. Neighbors also told Budde they had seen the woman defecating in their back yards as well as near a local [[Walgreens]] drugstore.<ref name=\"Washington Post story\" />\n\nBudde notified the [[Colorado Springs Police Department]] (CSPD), and made attempts on her own to end the jogger's defecations. She took pictures from the house, capturing a short brown-haired woman in a gray tank top and shorts. She put up a printed paper sign at the place near her house favored by the jogger, warning her that the police were aware of the situation, and asking her to stop.<ref name=\"Washington Post story\" />\n\nIn response, Budde said, the woman began changing the times she jogged by. She also ignored the note's pleas, running by it 15 times in one day before defecating near it again, according to Budde. The police have said she could face charges of [[Indecent exposure in the United States|indecent exposure]] and [[public defecation]] were they to identify and arrest her,<ref name=\"Washington Post story\" /> charges that, in the event of a conviction, might require that she [[Sex offender registries in the United States|register as a sex offender]].<ref name=\"KRDO spokesman story\">{{cite news|last=Clemens|first=Dana|title=Attorneys discuss rights to pooping in public after \"Mad Pooper\" video release|url=http://www.krdo.com/news/colorado-springs/mad-pooper-spokesman-explains/626058098|newspaper=[[KRDO-TV]]|date=September 27, 2017|accessdate=November 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOne officer, Lt. Howard Black, said he had never seen anything similar in his 35-year career in Colorado Springs. Like Budde, he admitted to the ''Post'' that it was amusing, but allowed for the possibility that the jogger might not be in full control of her actions. \"If it's a mental health issue, she'll still be held accountable, but we would want to get her help.\"<ref name=\"Washington Post story\" />\n\nIn September, almost two months after the jogger's defecations had begun, Budde went to KKTV, which reported on the story. Shortly afterwards, the ''Post'' wrote its article, and the story [[Viral phenomenon|went viral]].<ref name=\"Fox News October story\">{{cite news|title='Mad Pooper' inquiries should stop now, Colorado police say|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2017/10/04/mad-pooper-inquiries-should-stop-now-colorado-police-say.html|newspaper=[[Fox News]]|date=October 4, 2017|accessdate=November 1, 2017}}</ref> Through its [[Twitter]] account, [[Procter & Gamble]] made an offer to the jogger: if she turned herself in to police, they would give her a year's supply of the company's [[Charmin]] toilet paper for free.<ref name=\"P&G tweet\" />\n\n''[[Runner's World]]'' magazine ran a story with a headline asking the woman to stop. \"[A]s runners, we understand having a sudden emergency now and then. But when it becomes a habit, you need to change up your regimen.\" it wrote, giving readers the phone number for the CSPD to call if they believed they knew who the Mad Pooper was. The article further urged readers who might similarly be using public places to defecate on their runs to likewise stop. \"Pull up your pants, and take your business elsewhere. We do not know what else to say.\"<ref name=\"Runner's World editorial\">{{cite news|title=We Urge You 'Mad Pooper,' Stop Crapping in Your Neighbor's Yard|url=https://www.runnersworld.com/poop/we-urge-you-mad-pooper-stop-crapping-in-your-neighbors-yard|newspaper=[[Runner's World]]|date=September 19, 2017|accessdate=November 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSports news website ''[[Deadspin]]'' called the CSPD about the case so frequently the department asked them to stop in early October since they had nothing new to report.<ref name=\"Deadspin October story\">{{cite news|last=Redford|first=Patrick|title=Colorado Springs Police Beg Us To Stop Calling About The Mad Pooper, Who Is Still At Large|url=https://deadspin.com/colorado-springs-police-beg-us-to-stop-calling-about-th-1819084370|newspaper=[[Deadspin]]|date=October 3, 2017|accessdate=November 1, 2017}}</ref> Since then, police report, the woman appears to have stopped. However, despite the increase in publicity around the case the woman has not been identified.<ref name=\"Fox News October story\" />\n\n===Hoax spokesman===\n\nIn response to the news coverage, a video was posted on [[YouTube]] by someone who claimed to be a family member of the jogger, who he called \"Shirley\". He said she was sorry for repeatedly fouling the Buddes' yard. However he also attributed her inability to control herself to a [[traumatic brain injury]] and complications from recent [[Sex reassignment surgery (male-to-female)|sex reassignment surgery]].<ref name=\"KRDO spokesman story\" />\n\nBeyond that, however, he said it was irrelevant as she was not breaking any law. Her actions, he argued, were protected under the [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]], much like [[breastfeeding]]. Jeremy Loew, a criminal defense attorney consulted by Colorado Springs television station [[KRDO-TV]] emphatically rejected that claim. If the video truly was posted by \"Shirley\"'s family, Loew said, it was \"actually the worst thing the[y] could do. ... Maybe they thought the videos would make the situation go away, but they won't.\" The spokesman might even find himself called as a witness, Loew added.<ref name=\"KRDO spokesman story\" />\n\nA few days later, the man posted a second video in which he disclosed that the first one was a hoax.<ref name=\"Thrillist videos post\">{{cite news|last=Blum|first=Sam|title=The Mad Pooper Is Sorry For Repeatedly Pooping on Colorado Family's Lawn|url=https://www.thrillist.com/news/nation/mad-pooper-colorado-jogger-apologizes-for-pooping-on-familys-lawn|newspaper=[[Thrillist]]|date=September 30, 2017|accessdate=November 3, 2017}}</ref> He was later revealed to be DISOP TV, another YouTube user known for producing videos of flatulent pets, who admitted he made up the first video as \"satire.\" Both that video and the original were soon deleted from the site.<ref name=\"Deadspin October story\" />\n\n==Possible motives==\n\nSome news outlets went beyond reporting on the case to speculate as to what the reasons for the jogger's actions might be. Allison Feller, a writer for ''[[Women's Health (magazine)|Women's Health]]'', wondered if, like her, the Mad Pooper might be an avid runner who suffers from [[Crohn's disease]], a bowel inflammation whose symptoms can sometimes include an [[Fecal incontinence|inability to hold excrement long enough to reach a toilet]]. \"[M]y first thought upon seeing this headline\" she recalled, \"was, 'Oh my god, being the subject of this story is my greatest fear.'\"<ref name=\"Women's Health story\">{{cite news|last=Feller|first=Allison|title=Why I'm Not Laughing At That Viral Story About A Jogger Dubbed 'The Mad Pooper'|url=https://www.womenshealthmag.com/health/pooping-runner-mad-pooper|newspaper=[[Women's Health (magazine)|Women's Health]]|date=September 20, 2017|accessdate=November 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSometimes her disease left her in such pain as to be unable to run or even leave the house, Feller wrote. But when it did, she would experience symptoms very suddenly. \"[Crohn's] can strike when you least expect it. And when that happens, my intestines go from totally chill to totally explosive faster than you can even ''think'' about where the closest available restroom may be.\"<ref name=\"Women's Health story\" />\n\nFeller said she, too, took toilet paper and wipes with her every time she went for a run. \"I don't run with these things because I'm ''planning'' to use them. I run with them because I've learned to be prepared.\" She recounted many times when, due to public bathrooms being closed or too distant for her to reach she had had to seclude herself behind trees or under bridges in order to defecate. One time, she admitted, she had even had to use her pants.<ref name=\"Women's Health story\" />\n\n\"In an age where everyone is armed with a cell-phone camera, I am terrified of someone seeing me going to the bathroom in an unapproved place, then snapping a photo or video, and posting it for the world to see, LOL at, and comment on\", Feller wrote. She felt considerable shame over the way her disease inconvenienced her, and called the idea of experiencing [[public shaming]] on the Internet because of it \"paralyzing\". She warned readers who might not understand that feeling that they should not shame someone they see experiencing similar distress while running. \"[O]ne day, you, too, may eat a burrito that doesn't agree with your stomach, and you may find yourself in a non-bathroom bathroom situation.<ref name=\"Women's Health story\" />\n\nAt ''[[Psychology Today]]'', Dale Hartley, an associate professor of psychology at [[West Virginia University at Parkersburg]], was dismissive of the idea that the Mad Pooper might suffer from an ailment that caused those problems, since she was so public in her defecations and had shown no sign of changing her routine to avoid having to do so. Nor did he think she had any [[psychosis]], as she was \"too put-together to be out of touch with reality\" and kept to a regular schedule. \"We would not expect to see consistently organized, predictable behaviors in someone who has undergone a psychotic break,\" Hartley wrote.<ref name=\"Psychology Today blog post\">{{cite news|last=Hartley|first=Dale|title=What's Up with the Mad Pooper of Colorado Springs?|url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/machiavellians-gulling-the-rubes/201709/whats-the-mad-pooper-colorado-springs|newspaper=[[Psychology Today]]|date=September 20, 2017|accessdate=November 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIt was more likely, Hartley presumed, that some lesser psychological issues led to her actions. \"Is she an [[exhibitionism|exhibitionist]]?  I think this is closer to the truth\", he wrote. But even if this was so, he believed, the jogger's real problem was [[impulse control disorder]].\n{{quote|When they bare it all, exhibitionists have failed to control their impulse to reveal too much. The mad pooper's abnormal impulse may or may not be exhibitionism. She might instead feel an overwhelming urge to experience the sensation of a bowel movement out in the open air. Or to flaunt{{sic}} social rules, break the law, and get away with it (the same kind of thrill that a [[kleptomania]]c gets). So whatever itch she's scratching, I'd put my money on an impulse control disorder as the milk in her magnesia.}}\nHer choice of the same location for so many of her defecations, Hartley also speculated, may have been retaliation against the Buddes for having caught her in the act.<ref name=\"Psychology Today blog post\" />\n\n==Other instances==\n===The Newcastle Star Jumper===\nAn instance was reported by the [[Newcastle Chronicle]] in the [[United Kingdom]] of a female jogger caught defecating on CCTV in the outskirts of [[Newcastle-upon-Tyne]].<ref name=\"Shopkeeper furious after CCTV captures moment jogger appears to defecate outside store\">{{cite news|last=Johnson|first=Ian|title=Shopkeeper furious after CCTV captures moment jogger appears to defecate outside store|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/shopkeeper-furious-after-cctv-captures-16780061|newspaper=[[Newcastle Chronicle]]|date=August 22, 2019|accessdate=August 22, 2019}}</ref> Nicknamed the \"Star Jumper\" due to her performing [[star jumps]] after the act, she has not been identified.\n\n===The Lincoln Pooper===\n[[1011now]] reported an unknown female in [[Lincoln, Nebraska]] who'd been caught on camera pooing outside a local swimming pool.<ref name=\"Woman caught defecating near local swimming pool\">{{cite news|last=1011now|first=1011now|title=Woman caught defecating near local swimming pool|url=https://www.1011now.com/content/news/Woman-caught-defecating-near-local-swimming-pool-494011931.html|date=September 21, 2018|accessdate=September 21, 2018}}</ref>   Having been noted on multiple occasions to repeat the act before the pool opened and after it closed, at the time of the report she had yet to be identified.\n\n===The Brisbane Poo Jogger===\n[[News.com.au]] reported a male 64 year old male corporate executive nicknamed the \"Poo Jogger\" also caught on camera in [[Brisbane]], [[Australia]].<ref name=\"Doctors explain the possible reasons why people poo in public\">{{cite news|last=Brown|first=Vanessa|title=Doctors explain the possible reasons why people poo in public|url=https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/health-problems/psychologist-explains-the-possible-reasons-why-people-poo-in-public/news-story/46b58e6e5f6246323e9a75f52a6b470f|date=June 9, 2018|accessdate=June 9, 2018}}</ref> The suspect was caught after residents banded together after suspected multiple instances and photographed the culprit in the act.   Attracting worldwide interest, he was charged with creating a public nuisance.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Colorado|Law}}\n*[[2017 in the United States]]\n*[[Crime in Colorado]]\n*\"[[Broadcast Wagstaff School News]]\", a 2013 episode of the animated comedy series ''[[Bob's Burgers]]'' which featured an unidentified \"Mad Pooper\"\n*[[Runner's diarrhea]], which has led to runners defecating in public\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mad Pooper, The}}\n[[Category:Unidentified criminals]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Colorado]]\n[[Category:21st-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:American female criminals]]\n[[Category:Water supply and sanitation in the United States]]\n[[Category:Defecation]]\n[[Category:2017 in Colorado]]\n[[Category:2017 crimes in the United States]]\n[[Category:2010s in Colorado Springs]]\n", "name_user": "Grimes2", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOther instances:-first", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Mad_Pooper"}
{"title_page": "Pyap, South Australia", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox Australian place\n| type        = town\n| name        = Pyap\n| state       = sa\n| image       = File:River Murray, Great Pyap Landing(GN10424).jpg\n| caption     = Great Pyap Landing, ca. 1924\n| coordinates = {{coord|34.447419|S|140.496676|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coord_ref = <ref name=\"LMV\">{{cite web|title=Search results for \"Pyap, LOCB\" with the following datasets selected - 'Suburbs and Localities', 'Counties', 'Local Government Areas', 'Postcodes', 'SA Government Regions', 'Gazetter' and 'Roads' |url= http://location.sa.gov.au/viewer/?map=roads&x=140.50238&y=-34.43208&z=12&uids=19,2,11,18,20,105,136&pinx=140.498010&piny=-34.445940&pinTitle=Location&pinText=Pyap,+Locb |website=Location SA Map Viewer |publisher=Government of South Australia |accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref>\n| pop = 155\n| pop_year = {{CensusAU|2016}}\n| pop_footnotes = <ref name =\"Census2016SSC\">{{Census 2016 AUS | id = SSC41214 | name = Pyap (State Suburb) | quick = on | accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n| established              = \n| established_footnotes    = \n| postcode    = 5333\n| elevation   = \n| elevation_footnotes=\n| timezone = [[UTC9:30|ACST]]\n| utc = +9:30\n| timezone-dst = [[UTC10:30|ACST]]\n| utc-dst = +10:30\n| dist1       = \n| dir1        = \n| location1   = \n| dist2       = \n| dir2       = \n| location2   = \n\n\n\n| county      = [[County of Alfred|Alfred]]<ref name=\"LMV\"/>\n| region      = \n| lga         = \n| stategov    = [[Electoral district of Chaffey|Chaffey]]\n| fedgov      = [[Division of Barker|Barker]]\n\n| maxtemp = 24.0\n| maxtemp_footnotes = <ref name = climate>{{cite web|title=Monthly climate statistics: Summary statistics LOXTON RESEARCH CENTRE (nearest weather station) |url= http://www.bom.gov.au/climate/averages/tables/cw_024024.shtml |publisher=Commonwealth of Australia , Bureau of Meteorology|accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref>\n| mintemp = 9.1\n| mintemp_footnotes = <ref name = climate/>\t\n| rainfall = 263.2\n| rainfall_footnotes = <ref name = climate/>\n\n| near-n      = [[Spectacle Lake, South Australia|Spectacle Lake]]<br/>[[Gerard, South Australia|Gerard]]\n| near-ne     = [[Katarapko, South Australia|Katarapko]]\n| near-e      = [[Loxton, South Australia|Loxton]]\n| near-se     = \n| near-s      = [[Pyap West, South Australia|Pyap West]]\n| near-sw     = \n| near-w      = [[Wunkar, South Australia|Wunkar]]\n| near-nw     = [[New Residence, South Australia|New Residence]]<br/>[[Wappilka, South Australia|Wappilka]]\n|footnotes= Adjoining localities<ref name=\"LMV\"/>\n}}\n'''Pyap''' is a locality in the [[Riverland]] region of [[South Australia]]. It is on the left (south) bank of the [[Murray River]] about 7 km downstream from [[Loxton, South Australia|Loxton]]. It includes both flat land near the river and higher land away from it. The environment is dry, so vineyards and orchards are irrigated from the river. It lies on the [[Kingston-on-Murray, South Australia|Kingston]] Road from Loxton, at the junction with the [[Stott Highway]] towards [[Swan Reach, South Australia|Swan Reach]].\n\nPyap was first settled as a [[Village Settlements (South Australia)|Village Settlement]] in March 1894 with 94 members and 187 children on 9,145 acres (3,700 ha) and a total population of 388. The founding chairman was A. H. Brocklehurst and the secretary J. W. Rawnsley.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article25724820 |title=THE IRRIGATION COLONIES. |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |volume=XXXVI |issue=11098 |location=South Australia |date=14 May 1894 |accessdate=5 March 2018 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nIn about 1900 the government became tired of trying to keep the settlement going and when most of the village settlers abandoned the settlement, sold out lock, stock and barrel to a Mildura-Melbourne syndicate who appointed Mr. William Mitchell Plant as general manager. This firm continued to run the settlement with some success until 1913 when it eventually landed with [[Jack De Garis|C. J. DeGaris]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article109250195 |title=Pyap Irrigation Settlement |newspaper=[[Murray Pioneer And Australian River Record]] |location=South Australia |date=14 December 1939 |access-date=14 April 2020 |page=8 |via=Trove }}</ref> <ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article75390653 |title=PYAP. |newspaper=[[The Mildura Cultivator]] |issue=2197 |location=Victoria, Australia |date=3 March 1920 |accessdate=6 March 2018 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref>\n\nThe [[2016 Australian census]] which was conducted in August 2016 reports that Pyap had a population of 155 people.<ref name= \"Census2016SSC\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{District Council of Loxton Waikerie localities}}\n[[Category:Towns in South Australia]]\n{{SouthAustralia-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox Australian place\n| type        = town\n| name        = Pyap\n| state       = sa\n| image       = File:River Murray, Great Pyap Landing(GN10424).jpg\n| caption     = Great Pyap Landing, ca. 1924\n| coordinates = {{coord|34.447419|S|140.496676|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coord_ref = <ref name=\"LMV\">{{cite web|title=Search results for \"Pyap, LOCB\" with the following datasets selected - 'Suburbs and Localities', 'Counties', 'Local Government Areas', 'Postcodes', 'SA Government Regions', 'Gazetter' and 'Roads' |url= http://location.sa.gov.au/viewer/?map=roads&x=140.50238&y=-34.43208&z=12&uids=19,2,11,18,20,105,136&pinx=140.498010&piny=-34.445940&pinTitle=Location&pinText=Pyap,+Locb |website=Location SA Map Viewer |publisher=Government of South Australia |accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref>\n| pop = 155\n| pop_year = {{CensusAU|2016}}\n| pop_footnotes = <ref name =\"Census2016SSC\">{{Census 2016 AUS | id = SSC41214 | name = Pyap (State Suburb) | quick = on | accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n| established              = \n| established_footnotes    = \n| postcode    = 5333\n| elevation   = \n| elevation_footnotes=\n| timezone = [[UTC9:30|ACST]]\n| utc = +9:30\n| timezone-dst = [[UTC10:30|ACST]]\n| utc-dst = +10:30\n| dist1       = \n| dir1        = \n| location1   = \n| dist2       = \n| dir2       = \n| location2   = \n\n\n\n| county      = [[County of Alfred|Alfred]]<ref name=\"LMV\"/>\n| region      = \n| lga         = \n| stategov    = [[Electoral district of Chaffey|Chaffey]]\n| fedgov      = [[Division of Barker|Barker]]\n\n| maxtemp = 24.0\n| maxtemp_footnotes = <ref name = climate>{{cite web|title=Monthly climate statistics: Summary statistics LOXTON RESEARCH CENTRE (nearest weather station) |url= http://www.bom.gov.au/climate/averages/tables/cw_024024.shtml |publisher=Commonwealth of Australia , Bureau of Meteorology|accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref>\n| mintemp = 9.1\n| mintemp_footnotes = <ref name = climate/>\t\n| rainfall = 263.2\n| rainfall_footnotes = <ref name = climate/>\n\n| near-n      = [[Spectacle Lake, South Australia|Spectacle Lake]]<br/>[[Gerard, South Australia|Gerard]]\n| near-ne     = [[Katarapko, South Australia|Katarapko]]\n| near-e      = [[Loxton, South Australia|Loxton]]\n| near-se     = \n| near-s      = [[Pyap West, South Australia|Pyap West]]\n| near-sw     = \n| near-w      = [[Wunkar, South Australia|Wunkar]]\n| near-nw     = [[New Residence, South Australia|New Residence]]<br/>[[Wappilka, South Australia|Wappilka]]\n|footnotes= Adjoining localities<ref name=\"LMV\"/>\n}}\n'''Pyap''' is a locality in the [[Riverland]] region of [[South Australia]]. It is on the left (south) bank of the [[Murray River]] about 7 km downstream from [[Loxton, South Australia|Loxton]]. It includes both flat land near the river and higher land away from it. The environment is dry, so vineyards and orchards are irrigated from the river. It lies on the [[Kingston-on-Murray, South Australia|Kingston]] Road from Loxton, at the junction with the [[Stott Highway]] towards [[Swan Reach, South Australia|Swan Reach]].\n\nPyap was first settled as a [[Village Settlements (South Australia)|Village Settlement]] in March 1894 with 94 members and 187 children on 9,145 acres (3,700 ha) and a total population of 388. The founding chairman was A. H. Brocklehurst and the secretary J. W. Rawnsley.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article25724820 |title=THE IRRIGATION COLONIES. |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] |volume=XXXVI |issue=11098 |location=South Australia |date=14 May 1894 |accessdate=5 March 2018 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nMost of the village settlers abandoned the settlement and it was sold again by the government, eventually landing with [[Jack De Garis|C. J. DeGaris]] in 1913.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article75390653 |title=PYAP. |newspaper=[[The Mildura Cultivator]] |issue=2197 |location=Victoria, Australia |date=3 March 1920 |accessdate=6 March 2018 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref>\n\nThe [[2016 Australian census]] which was conducted in August 2016 reports that Pyap had a population of 155 people.<ref name= \"Census2016SSC\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{District Council of Loxton Waikerie localities}}\n[[Category:Towns in South Australia]]\n{{SouthAustralia-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Kjharris60", "label": "safe", "comment": "added details about syndicate who purchased", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyap,_South_Australia"}
{"title_page": "Lansdowne Bridge", "text_new": "{{about|the bridge in New South Wales|the bridge in Pakistan|Lansdowne Bridge Rohri}}\n{{Use dmy dates | date=September 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English | date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox bridge\n|bridge_name   = Lansdowne Bridge\n|image         = Lansdowne_Bridge_Sunset.jpg\n|image_size    = 270\n|caption       = Lansdowne Bridge carrying the Hume Highway over Prospect Creek\n| pushpin_map         = Australia Sydney\n| pushpin_relief      = `\n| pushpin_map_size    = 270\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in [[Sydney|greater Sydney]]\n|coordinates   = {{coord|-33.8902156386|150.9672223120|type:landmark_region:AU-NSW|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|official_name = \n| other_name   = Lennox Bridge\n|carries       = [[Hume Highway]] {{AUshield|NSW|A22}} {{bulleted list|[[Motor vehicle]]s|[[Pedestrian]]s}}\n|crosses       = [[Prospect Creek (New South Wales)|Prospect Creek, New South Wales]]\n|locale        = \n|maint         = \n|id            = \n|named_for     = [[Henry Petty-Fitzmaurice, 3rd Marquess of Lansdowne]]\n|designer      = [[David Lennox]]\n|design        = [[Arch bridge]]\n|material      = [[Sydney sandstone]]\n|spans         = \n|pierswater    = \n|mainspan      = {{convert|110|ft|m|order=flip}}\n|length        = {{convert|190|ft|m|order=flip}}\n|width         = {{convert|30|ft|m|order=flip}}\n|height        = \n|load          = \n|clearance     = {{convert|30|ft|m|order=flip}}\n|below         = \n|traffic       = \n|begin         = {{Start date|1834|January|01|df=yes}}\n|complete      = 1835\n|open          = {{Start date|1836|January|26|df=yes}}\n|closed        = \n|toll          = \n| mapframe            = yes\n| mapframe_zoom       = 14\n| mapframe_width      = \n| mapframe_height     = \n| mapframe_marker     = \n| mapframe_marker_color = \n| mapframe_lat        = \n| mapframe_long       = \n| map_caption         = \n| references          = <ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article32145336 |title=The Laytons, Female Emigrants. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Monitor]] |volume=VIII |issue=633 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=3 January 1834 |accessdate=11 September 2016 |page=2 (MORNING) |via=[[National Library of Australia]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12848457 |title=DOMESTIC INTELLIGENCE. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Herald]] |volume=III |issue=227 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=30 December 1833 |accessdate=30 December 2016 |page=2 |via=[[National Library of Australia]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12853766 |title=The Sydney Herald. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Herald]] |volume=VI |issue=442 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=21 January 1836 |accessdate=10 September 2016 |page=2 |via=[[National Library of Australia]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |title=Historic buildings vol III Liverpool and Campbelltown |date=1963 |publisher=Cumberland County Council |url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/28123654 |accessdate=10 September 2016 |pages=47\u201351}}</ref>\n| extra = \n{{Infobox designation list\n| embed                   = yes\n| designation1            = \n| designation1_offname    = \n| designation1_type       = \n| designation1_criteria   = \n| designation1_date       = \n| delisted1_date          = \n| designation1_partof     = \n| designation1_number     = \n| designation1_free1name  = \n| designation1_free1value = \n| designation1_free2name  = \n| designation1_free2value = \n| designation1_free3name  = \n| designation1_free3value = \n| designation2            = \n| designation2_offname    = \n| designation2_type       = \n| designation2_criteria   = \n| designation2_date       = \n| delisted2_date          = \n| designation2_partof     = \n| designation2_number     = \n| designation2_free1name  = \n| designation2_free1value = \n| designation2_free2name  = \n| designation2_free2value = \n| designation2_free3name  = \n| designation2_free3value = \n| designation3            = New South Wales State Heritage Register\n| designation3_offname    = Lansdowne Bridge; Lennox Bridge\n| designation3_type       = State heritage (built)\n| designation3_criteria   = ''[[New South Wales State Heritage Register#Criteria|undefined]]''\n| designation3_date       = 20 June 2000\n| delisted3_date          = \n| designation3_partof     = \n| designation3_number     = 01472\n| designation3_free1name  = Type\n| designation3_free1value = Road Bridge\n| designation3_free2name  = Category\n| designation3_free2value = Transport - Land\n| designation3_free3name  = Builders\n| designation3_free3value = [[David Lennox]]\n }}\n}}\nThe '''Lansdowne Bridge''' is a [[Heritage register|heritage-listed]] [[road bridge]] that carries the [[Hume Highway]] (A22) across the Prospect Creek at [[Lansvale, New South Wales|Lansvale]] in the [[City of Fairfield]] local government area of [[New South Wales]], Australia. It was designed and built from 1834 to 1836 by [[David Lennox]]. It is also known as '''Lennox Bridge'''. The property is owned by [[Roads and Maritime Services]], an [[government agency|agency]] of the [[Government of New South Wales]]. It was added to the [[New South Wales State Heritage Register]] on 20 June 2000.<ref name=nswshr-1472>{{cite NSW SHR|5051374|Lansdowne Bridge|hr=01472|fn=S91/01711|accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nOpened in 1836, the [[Sydney sandstone|sandstone]] [[arch bridge]] it has the largest [[Span (architecture)|span]] of any extant masonry bridge in Australia. The bridge is also considered to be one of the finest examples of [[Colonial architecture]] in Australia.<ref name=\"rms\">{{cite web|url=http://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/heritageapp/ViewHeritageItemDetails.aspx?ID=4301042|title=Lansdowne Bridge over Prospect Creek|date=7 July 2014|publisher=New South Wales Department of Roads and Maritime|accessdate=3 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923160251/http://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/heritageapp/ViewHeritageItemDetails.aspx?ID=4301042|archive-date=23 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nLansdowne bridge was designed and supervised by [[David Lennox]]. Born in Ayr, Scotland in 1788 David Lennox was trained as a stonemason. He worked on Telford's [[Menai, New South Wales|Menai]] Suspension Bridge at Anglesey in Wales and on [[Gloucester, New South Wales|Gloucester]] Bridge where he learnt the sound construction principles he used on his Colonial projects. He emigrated to Australia in 1832.<ref name=nswshr-1472/>\n\nHe immediately found employment as a mason with the government. While working at the [[New South Wales Legislative Council|Legislative Council]] Chambers in [[Macquarie Street, Sydney]], Lennox met the [[Surveyor General of New South Wales|Surveyor-General]] [[Thomas Mitchell (explorer)|Sir Thomas Mitchell]].<ref name=nswshr-1472/>\n\nThe Surveyor-General lost little time in submitting Lennox's credentials to the [[Governor of New South Wales|Governor]], describing him as \"a very well qualified person recently arrived in the Colony.\" Acting on Mitchell's recommendation, [[Richard Bourke|Governor Bourke]] provisionally appointed Lennox as a Sub-Inspector of Bridges at a salary of [[Australian pound|A\u00a3]]120 per annum. In June 1833 the position was confirmed by London as Superintendent of Bridges.<ref name=nswshr-1472/>\n\nIn 1832, the Surveyor-General at the time, [[Sir Thomas Mitchell]], commissioned Lennox for a sum of A\u00a31,083<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article2208948 |title=Votes and Proceedings. |newspaper=[[Sydney Gazette|The Sydney Gazette and New South Wales Advertiser]] |volume=XXX |issue=2192 |date=11 October 1832 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> to build a bridge at the intersection of Prospect Creek and Southern Street,<ref name = \"rms\"/><ref name=nswshr-1472/> which would replace the nearby \"Bowler's Bridge\" named after Lansdowne's local innkeeper.<ref name=\"ea\">{{cite web|url=https://www.engineersaustralia.org.au/portal/system/files/engineering-heritage-australia/nomination-title/Lennoxs_Lansdowne_Bridge_Nomination.pdf|title=Lennox's Lansdowne Bridge|publisher=The Institution of Engineers Australia|date=March 1986|access-date=6 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117033240/https://www.engineersaustralia.org.au/portal/system/files/engineering-heritage-australia/nomination-title/Lennoxs_Lansdowne_Bridge_Nomination.pdf|archive-date=17 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The sandstone used in designing the bridge was found in a quarry only {{convert|11|km}} from the proposed site of the bridge, allowing workers to row a [[punt (boat)|punt]] to transport the stone to the construction site.<ref name=nswshr-1472/>\n\nIn July 1833 Lennox told Mitchell of a mutiny that had occurred at the quarry while he had been away on an inspection tour. Some of the convicts had rebelled and had consumed the contents of a nearby liquor still. Returning to the camp drunk they threatened to kill the supervisor and destroy the camp and quarrying equipment. The police from [[Liverpool, New South Wales|Liverpool]] were called and arrested the offenders. Retribution at Liverpool Court was swift and savage; those who were spared the chain gang received up to fifty lashes of the \"cat\".<ref name=nswshr-1472/>\n\nOn 1 January 1834, Governor Bourke visited the site of the bridge to lay the foundation stone. Within hours of the laying of the inscription plate it was stolen. Lennox made arrangements to obtain a duplicate plate but the original was found and restored to the bridge.<ref name=nswshr-1472/> The [[foundation stone]] was laid on 1 January 1834. The bridge was constructed entirely by unskilled Australian convicts, despite Lennox's numerous requests to Mitchell for skilled labourers.<ref name=\"ea\"/> The bridge was completed a year later in 1835, and opened on 26 January 1836, the 48th anniversary of the [[Colony of New South Wales]], before a crowd of around 1,000.<ref name = \"rms\"/><ref name=\"ea\"/> Later, [[Richard Bourke]], the [[Governor of New South Wales]], wrote that the bridge had cost only A\u00a31,000 to build, compared to the A\u00a37,000 it would have taken to build a bridge of the same quality in England.<ref name=\"ea\"/>\n\nOn 7 June 1834 Lennox applied for more labourers, the bridge being at a stage where the centring could commence. This was the construction of a rigid timber frame to hold each stone in place until the arch became self-supporting. It was a critical process and any inaccuracies would cause instability or collapse the arch.<ref name=nswshr-1472/>\n\nUpon receiving a report that the bridge was nearing completion, Governor Bourke selected 26 January 1836 for the official opening date, as this coincided with the 48th anniversary of the Colony's foundation. The Lansdowne Bridge was not ready for several months as the Toll House was not complete. Once tolls started to be collected however, the bridge soon recovered its cost and in 1844 annual receipts were 685 pounds.<ref name=\"nswshr-1472-2378\">George, 1982</ref><ref name=\"nswshr-1472\" />\n\nIn 1956, the [[Government of New South Wales|New South Wales government]] duplicated the original bridge with a new concrete arch bridge parallel to the existing to carry southbound traffic of the [[Hume Highway]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Roadmakers, A History of Main Roads in New South Wales|last=|first=|publisher=Department of Main Roads|year=|isbn=0 7240 0439 4|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\nA large [[sandstone]] arched bridge spanning the Prospect Creek. The single arch has supporting [[buttress]]es. The clear [[Span (architecture)|span]] is 110 feet while the clearance above mean water level is 76 feet at the centre. It has curved abutments and approaches, while the [[parapet]]s and mouldings are simple and devoid of unnecessary ornamentation. Some of the radiating [[voussoir]]s are quite large in size measuring up to eight feet in length.<ref name=nswshr-1472-1349/><ref name=nswshr-1472/>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 1973, Australia recognized Lansdowne Bridge for being \"one of the finest examples of Colonial Architecture in Australia\".<ref name=\"rms\"/> In 1990, the Environmental Management Committee Fairfield Council confirmed that Lansdowne Bridge had the largest span of all masonry bridges in Australia and in 1992 that it was an example of excellent construction, which should be preserved.<ref name=\"rms\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fairfieldcity.nsw.gov.au/upload/uwshv69639/Hume_Hwy_No45_Lansdowne_Bridge.pdf |title=Historical Archaeological Sites \u2013 Lansdowne Bridge |publisher= Fairfield City Council |date= 15 July 1992 |access-date=3 November 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117022320/http://www.fairfieldcity.nsw.gov.au/upload/uwshv69639/Hume_Hwy_No45_Lansdowne_Bridge.pdf |archivedate=17 November 2015}}</ref> Lansdowne Bridge is also listed on the Register of the National Estate<ref>{{cite book |title=The Heritage of Australia: the illustrated register of the National Estate |publication-date=1981 |publisher=South Melbourne The Macmillan Company of Australia in association with the Australian Heritage Commission |author=[[Australian Heritage Commission]] |isbn=978-0-333-33750-9 |page=2/24 |url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/10431032 |access-date=12 September 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919065222/http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/10431032 |archive-date=19 September 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> and on the National Historic Engineering Landmark list.<ref name=\"ea\"/>\n\n== Heritage listing ==\nAs at 8 November 2000, Lansdowne Bridge is considered to be one of the finest examples of Colonial Architecture in Australia as well as David Lennox's masterpiece of design.<ref name=nswshr-1472-1349>{{cite book|last=Sheedy|first=D|date=1973|title=National Trust Classification Card - Lansdowne Bridge}}</ref> Lansdowne Bridge was built by convicts during 1834 to 1836. The sandstone arch has the largest span of any surviving masonry bridge in Australia. The size, appearance and durability make this bridge an outstanding example of colonial engineering.<ref name=nswshr-1472-2379>Environmental Management Committee. [[City of Fairfield|Fairfield Council]], 1990</ref><ref name=nswshr-1472/>\n\nLansdowne Bridge was listed on the [[New South Wales State Heritage Register]] on 20 June 2000 having satisfied the following criteria.<ref name=nswshr-1472/>\n\n'''The place is important in demonstrating the course, or pattern, of cultural or natural history in New South Wales.'''\n\nLansdowne Bridge is considered to be one of the finest examples of Colonial Architecture in Australia as well as David Lennox's masterpiece of design.<ref name=nswshr-1472-1349/> Lansdowne Bridge was built by convicts during 1834 to 1836.<ref name=nswshr-1472/><ref name=nswshr-1472-2379/>\n\n'''The place is important in demonstrating aesthetic characteristics and/or a high degree of creative or technical achievement in New South Wales.'''\n\nThe sandstone arch has the largest span of any surviving masonry bridge in Australia. The size, appearance and durability make this bridge an outstanding example of colonial engineering.<ref name=nswshr-1472/><ref name=nswshr-1472-2379/>\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|{{Portal|Transport|Engineering|New South Wales|Australian roads}}}}\n* [[Boothtown Aqueduct]]\n* [[List of bridges in Sydney]]\n* [[Lennox Bridge, Glenbrook]]\n* [[Lennox Bridge, Parramatta]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* {{cite web|author=|date=2007|title=Lansdowne Bridge|url=http://www.visitnsw.com.au/Operator.aspx?ProductId=9019502}}\n* {{cite web|author=Attraction Homepage|date=2007|title=Lansdowne Bridge|url=http://www.rta.nsw.gov.au/cgi-bin/index.cgi?action=heritage.show&id=4301042}}\n* {{cite book|author=Environmental Management Committee - Fairfield Council|date=1990|title=Heritage Conservation in Fairfield City - Meeting notes}}\n* {{cite book|last=George|first=Vance|date=1982|title=Fairfield: a History of the District}}\n* {{cite book|last=Sheedy|first=D.|date=1973|title=National Trust Classification Card - Lansdowne Bridge}}\n\n=== Attribution ===\n{{NSW-SHR-CC-contains|name=Lansdowne Bridge|dno=5051374|id=01472|year=2018|accessdate=2 June 2018}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Lansdowne Bridge, Sydney}}\n\n{{Bridges in Sydney |state=autocollapse}}\n{{Sydney landmarks|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:1836 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1835]]\n[[Category:Road bridges in New South Wales]]\n<!-- categories seem to need organising by groups, state, type, method, substance ... -->\n[[Category:Bridges in Sydney]]\n[[Category:Sandstone bridges in Australia]]\n[[Category:Stone arch bridges]]\n[[Category:New South Wales State Heritage Register]]\n[[Category:Lansvale, New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Articles incorporating text from the New South Wales State Heritage Register]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the bridge in New South Wales|the bridge in Pakistan|Lansdowne Bridge Rohri}}\n{{Use dmy dates | date=September 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English | date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox bridge\n|bridge_name   = Lansdowne Bridge\n|image         = Lansdowne_Bridge_Sunset.jpg\n|image_size    = 270\n|caption       = Lansdowne Bridge carrying the Hume Highway over Prospect Creek\n| pushpin_map         = Australia Sydney\n| pushpin_relief      = `\n| pushpin_map_size    = 270\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in [[Sydney|greater Sydney]]\n|coordinates   = {{coord|-33.8902156386|150.9672223120|type:landmark_region:AU-NSW|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|official_name = \n| other_name   = Lennox Bridge\n|carries       = [[Hume Highway]] {{AUshield|NSW|A22}} {{bulleted list|[[Motor vehicle]]s|[[Pedestrian]]s}}\n|crosses       = [[Prospect Creek (New South Wales)|Prospect Creek, New South Wales]]\n|locale        = \n|maint         = \n|id            = \n|named_for     = [[Henry Petty-Fitzmaurice, 3rd Marquess of Lansdowne]]\n|designer      = [[David Lennox]]\n|design        = [[Arch bridge]]\n|material      = [[Sydney sandstone]]\n|spans         = \n|pierswater    = \n|mainspan      = {{convert|110|ft|m|order=flip}}\n|length        = {{convert|190|ft|m|order=flip}}\n|width         = {{convert|30|ft|m|order=flip}}\n|height        = \n|load          = \n|clearance     = {{convert|30|ft|m|order=flip}}\n|below         = \n|traffic       = \n|begin         = {{Start date|1834|January|01|df=yes}}\n|complete      = 1835\n|open          = {{Start date|1836|January|26|df=yes}}\n|closed        = \n|toll          = \n| mapframe            = yes\n| mapframe_zoom       = 14\n| mapframe_width      = \n| mapframe_height     = \n| mapframe_marker     = \n| mapframe_marker_color = \n| mapframe_lat        = \n| mapframe_long       = \n| map_caption         = \n| references          = <ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article32145336 |title=The Laytons, Female Emigrants. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Monitor]] |volume=VIII |issue=633 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=3 January 1834 |accessdate=11 September 2016 |page=2 (MORNING) |via=[[National Library of Australia]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12848457 |title=DOMESTIC INTELLIGENCE. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Herald]] |volume=III |issue=227 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=30 December 1833 |accessdate=30 December 2016 |page=2 |via=[[National Library of Australia]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12853766 |title=The Sydney Herald. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Herald]] |volume=VI |issue=442 |location=New South Wales, Australia |date=21 January 1836 |accessdate=10 September 2016 |page=2 |via=[[National Library of Australia]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |title=Historic buildings vol III Liverpool and Campbelltown |date=1963 |publisher=Cumberland County Council |url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/28123654 |accessdate=10 September 2016 |pages=47\u201351}}</ref>\n| extra = \n{{Infobox designation list\n| embed                   = yes\n| designation1            = \n| designation1_offname    = \n| designation1_type       = \n| designation1_criteria   = \n| designation1_date       = \n| delisted1_date          = \n| designation1_partof     = \n| designation1_number     = \n| designation1_free1name  = \n| designation1_free1value = \n| designation1_free2name  = \n| designation1_free2value = \n| designation1_free3name  = \n| designation1_free3value = \n| designation2            = \n| designation2_offname    = \n| designation2_type       = \n| designation2_criteria   = \n| designation2_date       = \n| delisted2_date          = \n| designation2_partof     = \n| designation2_number     = \n| designation2_free1name  = \n| designation2_free1value = \n| designation2_free2name  = \n| designation2_free2value = \n| designation2_free3name  = \n| designation2_free3value = \n| designation3            = New South Wales State Heritage Register\n| designation3_offname    = Lansdowne Bridge; Lennox Bridge\n| designation3_type       = State heritage (built)\n| designation3_criteria   = ''[[New South Wales State Heritage Register#Criteria|undefined]]''\n| designation3_date       = 20 June 2000\n| delisted3_date          = \n| designation3_partof     = \n| designation3_number     = 01472\n| designation3_free1name  = Type\n| designation3_free1value = Road Bridge\n| designation3_free2name  = Category\n| designation3_free2value = Transport - Land\n| designation3_free3name  = Builders\n| designation3_free3value = [[David Lennox]]\n }}\n}}\nThe '''Lansdowne Bridge''' is a [[Heritage register|heritage-listed]] [[road bridge]] that carries the [[Hume Highway]] (A22) across the Prospect Creek at [[Lansvale, New South Wales|Lansvale]] in the [[City of Fairfield]] local government area of [[New South Wales]], Australia. It was designed and built from 1834 to 1836 by [[David Lennox]]. It is also known as '''Lennox Bridge'''. The property is owned by [[Roads and Maritime Services]], an [[government agency|agency]] of the [[Government of New South Wales]]. It was added to the [[New South Wales State Heritage Register]] on 20 June 2000.<ref name=nswshr-1472>{{cite NSW SHR|5051374|Lansdowne Bridge|hr=01472|fn=S91/01711|accessdate=2 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nOpened in 1836, the [[Sydney sandstone|sandstone]] [[arch bridge]] it has the largest [[Span (architecture)|span]] of any extant masonry bridge in Australia. The bridge is also considered to be one of the finest examples of [[Colonial architecture]] in Australia.<ref name=\"rms\">{{cite web|url=http://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/heritageapp/ViewHeritageItemDetails.aspx?ID=4301042|title=Lansdowne Bridge over Prospect Creek|date=7 July 2014|publisher=New South Wales Department of Roads and Maritime|accessdate=3 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923160251/http://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/heritageapp/ViewHeritageItemDetails.aspx?ID=4301042|archive-date=23 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nLansdowne bridge was designed and supervised by [[David Lennox]]. Born in Ayr, Scotland in 1788 David Lennox was trained as a stonemason. He worked on Telford's [[Menai, New South Wales|Menai]] Suspension Bridge at Anglesey in Wales and on [[Gloucester, New South Wales|Gloucester]] Bridge where he learnt the sound construction principles he used on his Colonial projects. He emigrated to Australia in 1832.<ref name=nswshr-1472/>\n\nHe immediately found employment as a mason with the government. While working at the [[New South Wales Legislative Council|Legislative Council]] Chambers in [[Macquarie Street, Sydney]], Lennox met the [[Surveyor General of New South Wales|Surveyor-General]] [[Thomas Mitchell (explorer)|Sir Thomas Mitchell]].<ref name=nswshr-1472/>\n\nThe Surveyor-General lost little time in submitting Lennox's credentials to the [[Governor of New South Wales|Governor]], describing him as \"a very well qualified person recently arrived in the Colony.\" Acting on Mitchell's recommendation, [[Richard Bourke|Governor Bourke]] provisionally appointed Lennox as a Sub-Inspector of Bridges at a salary of [[Australian pound|A\u00a3]]120 per annum. In June 1833 the position was confirmed by London as Superintendent of Bridges.<ref name=nswshr-1472/>\n\nIn 1832, the Surveyor-General at the time, [[Sir Thomas Mitchell]], commissioned Lennox for a sum of A\u00a31,083<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article2208948 |title=Votes and Proceedings. |newspaper=[[Sydney Gazette|The Sydney Gazette and New South Wales Advertiser]] |volume=XXX |issue=2192 |date=11 October 1832 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> to build a bridge at the intersection of Prospect Creek and Southern Street,<ref name = \"rms\"/><ref name=nswshr-1472/> which would replace the nearby \"Bowler's Bridge\" named after Lansdowne's local innkeeper.<ref name=\"ea\">{{cite web|url=https://www.engineersaustralia.org.au/portal/system/files/engineering-heritage-australia/nomination-title/Lennoxs_Lansdowne_Bridge_Nomination.pdf|title=Lennox's Lansdowne Bridge|publisher=The Institution of Engineers Australia|date=March 1986|access-date=6 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117033240/https://www.engineersaustralia.org.au/portal/system/files/engineering-heritage-australia/nomination-title/Lennoxs_Lansdowne_Bridge_Nomination.pdf|archive-date=17 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> The sandstone used in designing the bridge was found in a quarry only {{convert|11|km}} from the proposed site of the bridge, allowing workers to row a [[punt (boat)|punt]] to transport the stone to the construction site.<ref name=nswshr-1472/>\n\nIn July 1833 Lennox told Mitchell of a mutiny that had occurred at the quarry while he had been away on an inspection tour. Some of the convicts had rebelled and had consumed the contents of a nearby liquor still. Returning to the camp drunk they threatened to kill the supervisor and destroy the camp and quarrying equipment. The police from [[Liverpool, New South Wales|Liverpool]] were called and arrested the offenders. Retribution at Liverpool Court was swift and savage; those who were spared the chain gang received up to fifty lashes of the \"cat\".<ref name=nswshr-1472/>\n\nOn 1 January 1834, Governor Bourke visited the site of the bridge to lay the foundation stone. Within hours of the laying of the inscription plate it was stolen. Lennox made arrangements to obtain a duplicate plate but the original was found and restored to the bridge.<ref name=nswshr-1472/> The [[foundation stone]] was laid on 1 January 1834. The bridge was constructed entirely by unskilled Australian convicts, despite Lennox's numerous requests to Mitchell for skilled labourers.<ref name=\"ea\"/> The bridge was completed a year later in 1835, and opened on 26 January 1836, the 48th anniversary of the [[Colony of New South Wales]], before a crowd of around 1,000.<ref name = \"rms\"/><ref name=\"ea\"/> Later, [[Richard Bourke]], the [[Governor of New South Wales]], wrote that the bridge had cost only A\u00a31,000 to build, compared to the A\u00a37,000 it would have taken to build a bridge of the same quality in England.<ref name=\"ea\"/>\n\nOn 7 June 1834 Lennox applied for more labourers, the bridge being at a stage where the centring could commence. This was the construction of a rigid timber frame to hold each stone in place until the arch became self-supporting. It was a critical process and any inaccuracies would cause instability or collapse the arch.<ref name=nswshr-1472/>\n\nUpon receiving a report that the bridge was nearing completion, Governor Bourke selected 26 January 1836 for the official opening date, as this coincided with the 48th anniversary of the Colony's foundation. The Lansdowne Bridge was not ready for several months as the Toll House was not complete. Once tolls started to be collected however, the bridge soon recovered its cost and in 1844 annual receipts were 685 pounds.<ref name=\"nswshr-1472-2378\">George, 1982</ref><ref name=\"nswshr-1472\" />\n\nIn 1956, the [[Government of New South Wales|New South Wales government]] duplicated the original bridge with a new concrete arch bridge parallel to the existing to carry southbound traffic of the [[Hume Highway]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Roadmakers, A History of Main Roads in New South Wales|last=|first=|publisher=Department of Main Roads|year=|isbn=0 7240 0439 4|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\nA large [[sandstone]] arched bridge spanning the Prospect Creek. The single arch has supporting [[buttress]]es. The clear [[Span (architecture)|span]] is 110 feet while the clearance above mean water level is 76 feet at the centre. It has curved abutments and approaches, while the [[parapet]]s and mouldings are simple and devoid of unnecessary ornamentation. Some of the radiating [[voussoir]]s are quite large in size measuring up to eight feet in length.<ref name=nswshr-1472-1349/><ref name=nswshr-1472/>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 1973, Australia recognized Lansdowne Bridge for being \"one of the finest examples of Colonial Architecture in Australia\".<ref name=\"rms\"/> In 1990, the Environmental Management Committee Fairfield Council confirmed that Lansdowne Bridge had the largest span of all masonry bridges in Australia and in 1992 that it was an example of excellent construction, which should be preserved.<ref name=\"rms\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fairfieldcity.nsw.gov.au/upload/uwshv69639/Hume_Hwy_No45_Lansdowne_Bridge.pdf |title=Historical Archaeological Sites \u2013 Lansdowne Bridge |publisher= Fairfield City Council |date= 15 July 1992 |access-date=3 November 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117022320/http://www.fairfieldcity.nsw.gov.au/upload/uwshv69639/Hume_Hwy_No45_Lansdowne_Bridge.pdf |archivedate=17 November 2015}}</ref> Lansdowne Bridge is also listed on the Register of the National Estate<ref>{{cite book |title=The Heritage of Australia: the illustrated register of the National Estate |publication-date=1981 |publisher=South Melbourne The Macmillan Company of Australia in association with the Australian Heritage Commission |author=[[Australian Heritage Commission]] |isbn=978-0-333-33750-9 |page=2/24 |url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/10431032 |access-date=12 September 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919065222/http://trove.nla.gov.au/work/10431032 |archive-date=19 September 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> and on the National Historic Engineering Landmark list.<ref name=\"ea\"/>\n\n== Heritage listing ==\nAs at 8 November 2000, Lansdowne Bridge is considered to be one of the finest examples of Colonial Architecture in Australia as well as David Lennox's masterpiece of design.<ref name=nswshr-1472-1349>{{cite book|last=Sheedy|first=D|date=1973|title=National Trust Classification Card - Lansdowne Bridge}}</ref> Lansdowne Bridge was built by convicts during 1834 to 1836. The sandstone arch has the largest span of any surviving masonry bridge in Australia. The size, appearance and durability make this bridge an outstanding example of colonial engineering.<ref name=nswshr-1472-2379>Environmental Management Committee. [[City of Fairfield|Fairfield Council]], 1990</ref><ref name=nswshr-1472/>\n\nLansdowne Bridge was listed on the [[New South Wales State Heritage Register]] on 20 June 2000 having satisfied the following criteria.<ref name=nswshr-1472/>\n\n'''The place is important in demonstrating the course, or pattern, of cultural or natural history in New South Wales.'''\n\nLansdowne Bridge is considered to be one of the finest examples of Colonial Architecture in Australia as well as David Lennox's masterpiece of design.<ref name=nswshr-1472-1349/> Lansdowne Bridge was built by convicts during 1834 to 1836.<ref name=nswshr-1472/><ref name=nswshr-1472-2379/>\n\n'''The place is important in demonstrating aesthetic characteristics and/or a high degree of creative or technical achievement in New South Wales.'''\n\nThe sandstone arch has the largest span of any surviving masonry bridge in Australia. The size, appearance and durability make this bridge an outstanding example of colonial engineering.<ref name=nswshr-1472/><ref name=nswshr-1472-2379/>\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|{{Portal|Transport|Engineering|New South Wales|Australian roads}}}}\n* [[Boothtown Aqueduct]]\n* [[List of bridges in Sydney]]\n* [[Lennox Bridge, Parramatta]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* {{cite web|author=|date=2007|title=Lansdowne Bridge|url=http://www.visitnsw.com.au/Operator.aspx?ProductId=9019502}}\n* {{cite web|author=Attraction Homepage|date=2007|title=Lansdowne Bridge|url=http://www.rta.nsw.gov.au/cgi-bin/index.cgi?action=heritage.show&id=4301042}}\n* {{cite book|author=Environmental Management Committee - Fairfield Council|date=1990|title=Heritage Conservation in Fairfield City - Meeting notes}}\n* {{cite book|last=George|first=Vance|date=1982|title=Fairfield: a History of the District}}\n* {{cite book|last=Sheedy|first=D.|date=1973|title=National Trust Classification Card - Lansdowne Bridge}}\n\n=== Attribution ===\n{{NSW-SHR-CC-contains|name=Lansdowne Bridge|dno=5051374|id=01472|year=2018|accessdate=2 June 2018}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Lansdowne Bridge, Sydney}}\n\n{{Bridges in Sydney |state=autocollapse}}\n{{Sydney landmarks|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:1836 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1835]]\n[[Category:Road bridges in New South Wales]]\n<!-- categories seem to need organising by groups, state, type, method, substance ... -->\n[[Category:Bridges in Sydney]]\n[[Category:Sandstone bridges in Australia]]\n[[Category:Stone arch bridges]]\n[[Category:New South Wales State Heritage Register]]\n[[Category:Lansvale, New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Articles incorporating text from the New South W