{"title_page": "Jack Leach", "text_new": "{{short description|English cricketer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n|                name = Jack Leach\n|               image = Jack_Leach.jpg\n|             caption = Leach in 2013\n|             country = England\n|            fullname = Matthew Jack Leach\n|            nickname = Leachy,<ref name=\"MCC University profile\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mccuniversities.org/cardiff-glamorgan/player-profiles/jack-leach,215,PP.html |title=Jack Leach Profile |publisher=MCC Universities |accessdate=30 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102003915/http://www.mccuniversities.org/cardiff-glamorgan/player-profiles/jack-leach,215,PP.html |archive-date=2 November 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Nut<ref>https://www.ecb.co.uk/news/645649/sweet-as-a-nut-jack-leach-s-journey-to-england-s-test-squad</ref>\n|          birth_date = {{birth date and age|1991|6|22|df=y}}\n|         birth_place = [[Taunton]], [[Somerset]], England\n|            heightft =\n|          heightinch =\n|             heightm =\n|             batting = Left-handed\n|             bowling = [[Left-arm orthodox spin|Slow left-arm orthodox]]\n|                role = Bowler\n|       international = true\n|   internationalspan = 2018\u2013present\n|       testdebutdate = 30 March\n|       testdebutyear = 2018\n|    testdebutagainst = New Zealand\n|       lasttestdate  = 21 November\n|       lasttestyear  = 2019\n|     lasttestagainst = New Zealand\n|             testcap = 684\n|               club1 = [[Somerset County Cricket Club|Somerset]]\n|               year1 = {{nowrap|2010\u2013present}}\n|         clubnumber1 = 17\n|               club2 = [[Cardiff MCC University|Cardiff MCCU]]\n|               year2 = 2011\u20132012\n|               club3 = [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] (MCC)\n|               year3 = 2017\n|             columns = 3\n|             column1 = [[Test cricket|Test]]\n|            matches1 = 10\n|               runs1 = 220\n|            bat avg1 = 18.33\n|           100s/50s1 = 0/1\n|          top score1 = 92\n|         deliveries1 = 2,072\n|            wickets1 = 34\n|           bowl avg1 = 29.02\n|            fivefor1 = 1\n|             tenfor1 = 0\n|       best bowling1 = 5/83\n|  catches/stumpings1 = 5/\u2013\n|             column2 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n|            matches2 = 89\n|               runs2 = 1,123\n|            bat avg2 = 12.47\n|           100s/50s2 = 0/3\n|          top score2 = 92\n|         deliveries2 = 16,583\n|            wickets2 = 290\n|           bowl avg2 = 25.77\n|            fivefor2 = 20\n|             tenfor2 = 3\n|       best bowling2 = 8/85\n|  catches/stumpings2 = 37/\u2013\n|             column3 = [[List A cricket|LA]]\n|            matches3 = 16\n|               runs3 = 22\n|            bat avg3 = 7.33\n|           100s/50s3 = 0/0\n|          top score3 = 18\n|         deliveries3 = 824\n|            wickets3 = 21\n|           bowl avg3 = 30.52\n|            fivefor3 = 0\n|             tenfor3 = 0\n|       best bowling3 = 3/7\n|  catches/stumpings3 = 9/\u2013\n|                date = 13 March\n|                year = 2020\n|              source = https://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/455524.html ESPNcricinfo\n}}\n'''Matthew Jack Leach''' (born 22 June 1991) is an English [[cricket]]er who plays for [[Somerset County Cricket Club]] and [[England cricket team|England]]. A spin bowler, he bowls [[left-arm orthodox spin]], and bats left-handed. He made his [[First-class cricket|first-class]] debut for [[Cardiff MCC University]] against Somerset in 2012 before making his debut for Somerset in the tour match against the [[South Africa national cricket team|South Africans]] later in the summer. During the English summer of 2019, Leach became a national hero when he scored 1 not out single-handily guiding England home at Headingley. His performance ignited some Exeter boys to create jacks leach shirts, and create the famous song; leach me a pose, LEACHYS GOTTA LOOSEN UP.\n\n==Early life and education==\nLeach was born in [[Taunton]], England on 22 June 1991, and attended Trinity School, [[Bishop Fox's School]] and [[Richard Huish College, Taunton|Richard Huish College]] all in Taunton.<ref name=\"Cricinfo profile\">{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/player/455524.html |title=Jack Leach Profile |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=30 April 2013 }}</ref> He used to be employed to park trolleys at a branch of [[Sainsbury's]] supermarket in Taunton.<ref name=\"Maiden Five-wicket haul\">{{cite news |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2013/content/story/632900.html |last=Dobell |first=George |title=Warwickshire last pair thwart Somerset |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=28 April 2013 |accessdate=30 April 2013 }}</ref> At the age of 14, Leach was diagnosed with [[Crohn's disease]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/46046486 |title=Jack Leach on England, DJing at Jos Buttler's wedding, Crohn's & trolleys |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=2 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/28192460/jack-leach-hospitalised-bout-gastroenteritis |title=Jack Leach hospitalised by bout of gastroenteritis |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Cricket career==\nLeach graduated from the [[Somerset County Cricket Club]] academy in the summer of 2010,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.somersetcountycc.co.uk/player/jack-leach/ |title=Jack Leach \u2013 Squad |publisher=Somerset County Cricket Club |accessdate=30 April 2013 }}</ref> prior to signing a professional contract with Somerset. Leach represented [[Dorset County Cricket Club]] in the 2010 [[Minor Counties Cricket Championship]], and bowled his side to victory in the final against [[Lincolnshire County Cricket Club|Lincolnshire]] taking 6/21 in their second innings.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/266/266298.html |title=Dorset v Lincolnshire in 2010 |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=30 April 2013 }}</ref> Leach completed his degree at the [[University of Wales Institute, Cardiff]] in sports coaching.<ref name=\"MCC University profile\"/> Whilst attending university Leach represented [[Cardiff MCC University|Cardiff MCCU]] in 2011 and 2012 making his first-class debut against his county side Somerset in March 2012, bowling 41 overs but failing to take a wicket as Somerset amassed 642/3[[Declaration and forfeiture|d]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/542465.html |title=Somerset v Cardiff MCCU at Taunton, 31 March \u2013 2 April, 2012 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=30 April 2013 }}</ref>\n\nLeach made his Somerset debut in a two-day match against the [[South African cricket team in England in 2012|touring]] [[South Africa national cricket team|South Africans]] in July 2012, claiming the prized wicket of [[Hashim Amla]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-south-africa-2012/content/story/571791.html |title=Duminy finds valuable form ahead of Tests |last=Moonda |first=Firdose |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=10 July 2012 |accessdate=30 April 2013 }}</ref> He made his first-class debut for Somerset in the [[2012 County Championship]] match against [[Lancashire County Cricket Club|Lancashire]] in August 2012,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thisisbristol.co.uk/Spinner-Leach-lined-Somerset-debut-Liverpool/story-16623597-detail/story.html |title=Spinner Leach is lined up for Somerset debut in Liverpool |publisher=The Bristol Post |date=1 August 2012 |accessdate=30 April 2013 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130505155456/http://www.thisisbristol.co.uk/Spinner-Leach-lined-Somerset-debut-Liverpool/story-16623597-detail/story.html |archive-date=5 May 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> the rain affected match finished as a draw with Leach claiming [[Kyle Hogg]] as his maiden first-class wicket.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2012/content/story/575419.html |title=Prince turns match on its head |last=Hodgson |first=Myles |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=3 August 2012 |accessdate=30 April 2013 }}</ref> Further opportunities in the first team were limited for the rest of the 2012 season with the signing of Pakistani spinner [[Abdur Rehman (cricketer, born 1980)|Abdur Rehman]], and Leach only featured in one further County Championship match and three matches in the [[2012 Clydesdale Bank 40]], but ended the season ninth in the national first-class averages with 12 wickets at 18.83 runs apiece.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.somersetcountycc.co.uk/2012/09/jacks-off-to-play-grade-cricket-in-brisbane/ |title=Jack's off to play Grade Cricket in Brisbane |publisher=Somerset County Cricket Club |date=25 September 2012 |accessdate=30 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920235713/http://www.somersetcountycc.co.uk/2012/09/jacks-off-to-play-grade-cricket-in-brisbane/ |archive-date=20 September 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Leach spent the 2012\u201313 winter playing [[grade cricket]] for [[Valley District Cricket Club]] in [[Brisbane]], Australia, helping his side to win the T20 competition.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.somersetcountycc.co.uk/2013/03/jack-leach-aiming-for-championship-opener-against-durham/ |title=Jack Leach aiming for Championship opener against Durham |publisher=Somerset County Cricket Club |date=24 March 2013 |accessdate=30 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130526212128/http://www.somersetcountycc.co.uk/2013/03/jack-leach-aiming-for-championship-opener-against-durham/ |archive-date=26 May 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nLeach returned to Somerset for pre-season on a summer contract and played his first [[2013 County Championship|Championship]] game of the season against [[Warwickshire County Cricket Club|Warwickshire]] due to an injury to first choice spinner [[George Dockrell]]; he took his maiden five-wicket haul in the second innings, with 24 of his 44 overs being maidens.<ref name=\"Maiden Five-wicket haul\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/22339873 |title=Jack Leach: Somerset spinner frustrated by Bears draw |publisher=BBC Sport |date=30 April 2013 |accessdate=30 April 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nOn 14 February 2018, while playing for the [[England Lions (cricket team)|England Lions]] against [[West Indies A]], Leach achieved match figures of 8-110; in doing so, he beat the previous best figures by an England Lions spinner ([[Graeme Swann]]'s 8-156).<ref>{{cite web|title=Jack Leach claims best figures by England Lions spinner during defeat to West Indies A|url=http://www.skysports.com/cricket/news/12173/11250662/jack-leach-claims-best-figures-by-england-lions-spinner-during-defeat-to-west-indies-a|website=Sky Sports|accessdate=14 February 2018|date=14 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 2018, he was called up to England's [[Test cricket|Test]] squad for the [[English cricket team in New Zealand in 2017\u201318|tour of New Zealand]] as an injury replacement for [[Mason Crane]].<ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/cricket/2018/03/16/england-call-jack-leach-replace-injured-mason-crane/</ref> He made his debut in the second Test in [[Christchurch]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/1115781.html|title=2nd Test, England tour of Australia and New Zealand at Christchurch, Mar 30 - Apr 3 2018|work=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=30 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn an unusual circumstance, with 1 over left to play during [[English cricket team in Sri Lanka in 2018\u201319|a Test match against Sri Lanka]] on 15 November 2018, Leach opened England's innings as a [[nightwatchman (cricket)|nightwatchman]], surviving till stumps. He was dismissed for 1 off 11 balls the next morning.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/18602/commentary/1140386/sri-lanka-vs-england-2nd-test-eng-in-sl-2018-19|title=2nd Test, England tour of Sri Lanka at Kandy, Nov 14-18 2018|work=ESPN Cricinfo|accessdate=16 November 2018}}</ref> In July 2019, in the one-off Test [[Irish cricket team in England in 2019|against Ireland]], Leach was once again the nightwatchman for England, batting for a single over at the close of day one.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/49114455 |title=England v Ireland: Jack Leach makes 92 before hosts collapse in Lord's Test |work=BBC Sport |accessdate=26 July 2019}}</ref> England won the Test by 143 runs, with Leach scoring 92 runs, which earned him the man of the match award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/series/18774/report/1152839/day/3/england-vs-ireland-only-test-ireland-tour-of-england-2019 |title=Chris Woakes and Stuart Broad wreck Ireland dream in a session |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=26 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe was then recalled for the second Ashes test at [[Lord's|Lords]], on 14 August 2019, where he scored 6 not out in the first innings and took 1-19 and 3-37 in Australia's first and second innings respectively. England drew the match.\n\nLeach scored 1 run in a partnership of 76 with [[Ben Stokes]], to help [[England National Cricket Team|England]] win the third Ashes test at [[Headingley Stadium|Headingley]], by 1 wicket.\n\nLeach gained a cult following over the summer of 2019, with his glasses being a contributing factor. He regularly cleans them through his innings, and has received free Specsavers glasses for life following his heroics supporting Ben Stokes in the dramatic Headingley test.<ref>{{cite web |title=Specsavers to offer England's Jack Leach 'free glasses for life' |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/cricket/specsavers-to-offer-englands-jack-leach-free-glasses-for-life-after-ben-stokes-tweet-a4221241.html |website=Evening Standard |language=en |date=25 August 2019}}</ref> This cult reputation was enhanced by his behaviour off the pitch, such as leading some of the England team out to recreate his famous run at Headingley after the match.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dhingra |first1=Himanshu |title=Watch: Jack Leach recreates that single in 76 run partnership with Ben Stokes |url=https://www.livemint.com/sports/cricket-news/watch-jack-leach-recreates-that-single-in-76-run-partnership-with-ben-stokes-1566920791740.html |website=Mint |language=en |date=27 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of people diagnosed with Crohn's disease]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cricinfo|id=455524}}\n\n{{Somerset County Cricket Club squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leach, Jack}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Taunton]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Cardiff Metropolitan University]]\n[[Category:English cricketers]]\n[[Category:England Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:Dorset cricketers]]\n[[Category:Cardiff MCCU cricketers]]\n[[Category:Somerset cricketers]]\n[[Category:Marylebone Cricket Club cricketers]]\n[[Category:People with Crohn's disease]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English cricketer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n|                name = Jack Leach\n|               image = Jack_Leach.jpg\n|             caption = Leach in 2013\n|             country = England\n|            fullname = Matthew Jack Leach\n|            nickname = Leachy,<ref name=\"MCC University profile\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mccuniversities.org/cardiff-glamorgan/player-profiles/jack-leach,215,PP.html |title=Jack Leach Profile |publisher=MCC Universities |accessdate=30 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102003915/http://www.mccuniversities.org/cardiff-glamorgan/player-profiles/jack-leach,215,PP.html |archive-date=2 November 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Nut<ref>https://www.ecb.co.uk/news/645649/sweet-as-a-nut-jack-leach-s-journey-to-england-s-test-squad</ref>\n|          birth_date = {{birth date and age|1991|6|22|df