{"title_page": "Sarah Maldoror", "text_new": "{{short description|French film director}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Sarah Maldoror\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birthname          = Sarah Durados\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|df=y|1929|7|19}}\n| birth_place        = [[Condom, Gers|Condom]], France\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|df=y|2020|4|13|1929|7|19}}\n| death_place        = [[Saint-Denis, Seine-Saint-Denis|Saint-Denis]], France\n| occupation         = Film director, writer\n| yearsactive        = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n}}\n\n'''Sarah Maldoror''' (19 July 1929 \u2212 13 April 2020)<ref>https://www.publico.pt/2020/04/13/culturaipsilon/noticia/morreu-sarah-maldoror-pioneira-cinema-africano-1912082</ref> was a French filmmaker of French West Indies  descent.\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn '''Sarah Durados''' in 1929 in [[Condom, Gers]], the daughter of emigrants from [[Guadeloupe]], she chose her artist's name in remembrance of ''[[Les Chants de Maldoror]]'' by [[Lautr\u00e9amont]].\n\nShe attended a drama school in Paris. Together with her husband, Angolan nationalist [[M\u00e1rio Pinto de Andrade]], she received a scholarship and studied film with [[Mark Donskoi]] in Moscow in 1961\u201362 where she met [[Ousmane Semb\u00e8ne]].<ref name=\"1997 interview\">[http://www.africanwomenincinema.org/AFWC/Maldoror.html \"Sarah Maldoror, Guadeloupe, France\", translation of interview at 15th edition of FESPACO, February 1997, Ouagadougou, Burkina Faso; originally published in ''Sisters of the Screen: Women of Africa on Film Video and Television'', Africa World Press, Trenton, NJ, 2000.]</ref> She is best known for her feature film ''[[Sambizanga (film)|Sambizanga]]'' (1972) on the [[Portuguese Colonial War|1961\u20131974 war]] in [[Angola]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=pFQQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=MowDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6244,5229471&dq=sarah-maldoror&hl=en|title=Angola: Brutality Betrayal|date=6 December 1973|work=[[Village Voice]]|accessdate=5 August 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAfter her studies, Sarah Maldoror, worked as an assistant on [[Gillo Pontecorvo]]'s acclaimed film, ''[[The Battle of Algiers (film)|The Battle of Algiers]]'' (1966).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sayre|first1=Nora|title=Movie Review \u2013 Sambizanga (1973)|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9904EFDA1F3CE13BBC4A51DFB7678388669EDE|accessdate=29 January 2016|work=The New York Times|date=22 November 1973|ref=nyt1973}}</ref> She also worked as an assistant to Algerian director Ahmed Lallem.\n\nMaldoror's short film, ''Monangambee'' (1968), was set in Angola, based on a story by Angolan writer [[Jos\u00e9 Luandino Vieira]]. This 17-minute-long film's title, ''Monangamb\u00e9e'', refers to the call used by Angolan anti-colonial activists to signal a village meeting. The film was shot with amateur actors in Algeria. It tells the story of a poor woman who visits her husband, who is imprisoned in the city of Luanda.<ref>{{cite web|last=Dembrow |first=Michael |title=Sambizanga and Sarah Maldoror |url=http://spot.pcc.edu/~mdembrow/sambizanga.htm |accessdate=22 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315120913/http://spot.pcc.edu/~mdembrow/sambizanga.htm |archivedate=15 March 2012 }}</ref> The film was selected for the [[Director's Fortnight]] at Cannes in 1971, representing Angola.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sambizanga Review|url=http://mubi.com/films/sambizanga|publisher=MUBI|accessdate=22 August 2012}}</ref>{{failed verification|date=August 2015}}\n\nHer first feature film, ''[[Sambizanga (film)|Sambizanga]]'', was also based on a story by Vieira.\n\nMaldoror is one of the first women to direct a feature film in Africa; therefore, her work is often included in studies of the role of African women in African cinema.\n\nMaldoror died on April 13, 2020, at the age of 90, from [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in France]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://la1ere.francetvinfo.fr/coronavirus-deces-de-la-realisatrice-sarah-maldoror-a-91-ans-822570.html|title=Sarah Maldoror, pionni\u00e8re du cin\u00e9ma panafricain, d\u00e9c\u00e8de du coronavirus|language=fr|website=Outre-mer la 1\u00e8re}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* Maldoror won a [[Tanit d'or]] at the 1972 [[Carthage Film Festival]]\n* Maldoror received the [[National Order of Merit (France)]] from the Government of France<ref>{{cite web|title=Remise de l'ordre national du m\u00e9rite \u00e0 Sarah Maldoror par Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric {{sic|Mitt|erand|hide=y}}|url=http://vimeo.com/26966681|accessdate=22 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n*''Monangamb\u00e9'', 1968\n*''Des fusils pour Banta'' (Guns for Banta), 1970\n*''Carnaval en Guin\u00e9e-Bissau'' (Carnival in Guinea-Bissau), 1971\n*''[[Sambizanga (film)|Sambizanga]]'', 1972\n*''Un carneval dans le Sahel'' (Carnival in Sahel), 1977\n*''Folgo, Ile de Feu''\n*''Et les chiens se taisaient'' (And the dogs kept silent)\n*''Un homme, une terre'' (A man, a country)\n*''La Basilique de Saint-Denis''\n*''Un dessert pour Constance'', 1983\n*''Le cimeti\u00e8re du P\u00e8re Lachaise''\n*''Miro''\n*''Lauren''\n*''Robert Lapoujade, peintre''\n*''[[Toto Bissainthe]], Chanteuse''\n*''[[Ren\u00e9 Depestre]], po\u00e8te''\n*''L'h\u00f4pital de Leningrad'', 1983\n*''La litt\u00e9rature tunisienne de la Biblioth\u00e8que nationale''\n*''Un s\u00e9n\u00e9galias en Normandie''\n*''[[Robert Doisneau]], photographe''\n*''Le racisme au quotidien'' (Daily life racism), 1983\n*''Le passager du Tassili'' (The Tassili passenger), 1987\n*''[[Aim\u00e9 C\u00e9saire]], le masque des mots'' (Aim\u00e9 C\u00e9saire, word as masks), 1986\n*''[[Emmanuel Ungaro]], couturier''\n*''[[Louis Aragon]] \u2013 Un masque \u00e0 Paris''\n*''Vlady, peintre''\n*''[[L\u00e9on Damas|L\u00e9on G. Damas]]'', 1995\n*''L'enfant-cin\u00e9ma'', 1997\n*''La tribu du bois de l'\u00e9'' (In the time of people)\n\n==Documentary about Sarah Maldoror==\n*''Sarah Maldoror ou la nostalgie de l\u2019utopie'' by [[Anne Laure Folly]], France /Togo, 1998.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Women's Cinema]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0539275}}\n\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in France}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maldoror, Sarah}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:French film directors]]\n[[Category:French women film directors]]\n[[Category:French people of Guadeloupean descent]]\n[[Category:Knights of the National Order of Merit (France)]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in France]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French film director}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Sarah Maldoror\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birthname          = Sarah Durados\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|df=y|1929|7|19}}\n| birth_place        = [[Condom, Gers|Condom]], France\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|df=y|2020|4|13|1929|7|19}}\n| death_place        = [[Saint-Denis, Seine-Saint-Denis|Saint-Denis]], France\n| occupation         = Film director, writer\n| yearsactive        = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n}}\n\n'''Sarah Maldoror''' (19 July 1929 \u2212 13 April 2020)<ref>https://www.publico.pt/2020/04/13/culturaipsilon/noticia/morreu-sarah-maldoror-pioneira-cinema-africano-1912082</ref> was a French filmmaker of French West Indies  descent.\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn '''Sarah Durados''' in 1929 in [[Condom, Gers]], the daughter of emigrants from [[Guadeloupe]], she chose her artist's name in remembrance of ''[[Les Chants de Maldoror]]'' by [[Lautr\u00e9amont]].\n\nShe attended a drama school in Paris. Together with her husband, Angolan nationalist [[M\u00e1rio Pinto de Andrade]], she received a scholarship and studied film with [[Mark Donskoi]] in Moscow in 1961\u201362 where she met [[Ousmane Semb\u00e8ne]].<ref name=\"1997 interview\">[http://www.africanwomenincinema.org/AFWC/Maldoror.html \"Sarah Maldoror, Guadeloupe, France\", translation of interview at 15th edition of FESPACO, February 1997, Ouagadougou, Burkina Faso; originally published in ''Sisters of the Screen: Women of Africa on Film Video and Television'', Africa World Press, Trenton, NJ, 2000.]</ref> She is best known for her feature film ''[[Sambizanga (film)|Sambizanga]]'' (1972) on the [[Portuguese Colonial War|1961\u20131974 war]] in [[Angola]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=pFQQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=MowDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6244,5229471&dq=sarah-maldoror&hl=en|title=Angola: Brutality Betrayal|date=6 December 1973|work=[[Village Voice]]|accessdate=5 August 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAfter her studies, Sarah Maldoror, worked as an assistant on [[Gillo Pontecorvo]]'s acclaimed film, ''[[The Battle of Algiers (film)|The Battle of Algiers]]'' (1966).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sayre|first1=Nora|title=Movie Review \u2013 Sambizanga (1973)|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9904EFDA1F3CE13BBC4A51DFB7678388669EDE|accessdate=29 January 2016|work=The New York Times|date=22 November 1973|ref=nyt1973}}</ref> She also worked as an assistant to Algerian director Ahmed Lallem.\n\nMaldoror's short film, ''Monangambee'' (1968), was set in Angola, based on a story by Angolan writer [[Jos\u00e9 Luandino Vieira]]. This 17-minute-long film's title, ''Monangamb\u00e9e'', refers to the call used by Angolan anti-colonial activists to signal a village meeting. The film was shot with amateur actors in Algeria. It tells the story of a poor woman who visits her husband, who is imprisoned in the city of Luanda.<ref>{{cite web|last=Dembrow |first=Michael |title=Sambizanga and Sarah Maldoror |url=http://spot.pcc.edu/~mdembrow/sambizanga.htm |accessdate=22 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315120913/http://spot.pcc.edu/~mdembrow/sambizanga.htm |archivedate=15 March 2012 }}</ref> The film was selected for the [[Director's Fortnight]] at Cannes in 1971, representing Angola.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sambizanga Review|url=http://mubi.com/films/sambizanga|publisher=MUBI|accessdate=22 August 2012}}</ref>{{failed verification|date=August 2015}}\n\nHer first feature film, ''[[Sambizanga (film)|Sambizanga]]'', was also based on a story by Vieira.\n\nMaldoror is one of the first women to direct a feature film in Africa; therefore, her work is often included in studies of the role of African women in African cinema.\n\nMaldoror died on April 13, 2020, at the age of 90, from [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in France]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://la1ere.francetvinfo.fr/coronavirus-deces-de-la-realisatrice-sarah-maldoror-a-91-ans-822570.html|title=Sarah Maldoror, pionni\u00e8re du cin\u00e9ma panafricain, d\u00e9c\u00e8de du coronavirus|language=fr|website=Outre-mer la 1\u00e8re}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* Maldoror won a [[Tanit d'or]] at the 1972 [[Carthage Film Festival]]\n* Maldoror received the [[National Order of Merit (France)]] from the Government of France<ref>{{cite web|title=Remise de l'ordre national du m\u00e9rite \u00e0 Sarah Maldoror par Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric {{sic|Mitt|erand|hide=y}}|url=http://vimeo.com/26966681|accessdate=22 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n*''Monangamb\u00e9'', 1968\n*''Des fusils pour Banta'' (Guns for Banta), 1970\n*''Carnaval en Guin\u00e9e-Bissau'' (Carnival in Guinea-Bissau), 1971\n*''[[Sambizanga (film)|Sambizanga]]'', 1972\n*''Un carneval dans le Sahel'' (Carnival in Sahel), 1977\n*''Folgo, Ile de Feu''\n*''Et les chiens se taisaient'' (And the dogs kept silent)\n*''Un homme, une terre'' (A man, a country)\n*''La Basilique de Saint-Denis''\n*''Un dessert pour Constance'', 1983\n*''Le cimeti\u00e8re du P\u00e8re Lachaise''\n*''Miro''\n*''Lauren''\n*''Robert Lapoujade, peintre''\n*''[[Toto Bissainthe]], Chanteuse''\n*''[[Ren\u00e9 Depestre]], po\u00e8te''\n*''L'h\u00f4pital de Leningrad'', 1983\n*''La litt\u00e9rature tunisienne de la Biblioth\u00e8que nationale''\n*''Un s\u00e9n\u00e9galias en Normandie''\n*''[[Robert Doisneau]], photographe''\n*''Le racisme au quotidien'' (Daily life racism), 1983\n*''Le passager du Tassili'' (The Tassili passenger), 1987\n*''[[Aim\u00e9 C\u00e9saire]], le masque des mots'' (Aim\u00e9 C\u00e9saire, word as masks), 1986\n*''[[Emmanuel Ungaro]], couturier''\n*''[[Louis Aragon]] \u2013 Un masque \u00e0 Paris''\n*''Vlady, peintre''\n*''[[L\u00e9on Damas|L\u00e9on G. Damas]]'', 1995\n*''L'enfant-cin\u00e9ma'', 1997\n*''La tribu du bois de l'\u00e9'' (In the time of people)\n\n==Documentary about Sarah Maldoror==\n*''Sarah Maldoror ou la nostalgie de l\u2019utopie'' by [[Anne Laure Folly]], France /Togo, 1998.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Women's Cinema]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0539275}}\n\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in France}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maldoror, Sarah}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:French film directors]]\n[[Category:French women film directors]]\n[[Category:Knights of the National Order of Merit (France)]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in France]]\n", "name_user": "Inter&anthro", "label": "safe", "comment": "says it in the article", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sarah_Maldoror"}
